ant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\"</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to American Lithographic. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\".)</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on nine different magazine covers from 1923 to 1932. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York area]] from 1909 to 1931. Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as more commercially, than creatively inspired. Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic sentiment to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photograph), 26 (description). Scroll far downward. It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]] ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689, 691. Another source with photo/desc.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click icon>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature.</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''Ladies' Home Journal'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing those racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no in-print proof. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921 newsgravure section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Lithographic, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref><ref name=\"reading\">''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The cover model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as originally known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts'', edited by Copeland, 1902 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>[https://www.masslive.com/living/index.ssf/2012/11/stephen_jendrysik_chicopee_has_history_as_a_city_that_works.html \"Chicopee Has History\"]. Posted online by Jendrysik, Nov. 7, 2012. Its source was ''Economic History of a Factory Town'', [[Vera Shlakman]], 1935. They struggled to survive the [[Great Depression]]. It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]] (1940),<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> which became known as [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal Inc.]] (1961). Its name changed to [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986), through a merger. This company sold its tire division to [[Michelin]] (1990). The Fisk Tire brand was discontinued in 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> [[Michelin]] started reproducing them in 1996. This revitalized brand was sold through [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2013).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort\" by Dave Zielasko. Excerpts: \"'We needed a dedicated line with a dedicated inventory' ... It so happened the Fisk name, unused since the [1970s] was available.\"</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Tire Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debuted 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized,\" March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12. The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, suitable for framing.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. They were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of promotional children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were subtitled \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These items were either freebies, or giveaways with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. His smile version is mentioned by [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]], after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He previously worked as a brokerage clerk.</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print).</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked as one of the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]] from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #228.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\"</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to American Lithographic. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\".)</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "JimPercy", "label": "safe", "comment": "word change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Martin_(illustrator)"}
{"title_page": "Betrayal at Krondor", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title = Betrayal at Krondor\n|image = Betrayal at Krondor6.jpg\n|developer = [[Dynamix]]\n|publisher = [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra On-Line]]\n|director = John Cutter\n|designer = John Cutter<br>[[Neal Hallford]]\n|programmer = Nels Bruckner\n|artist = Michael McHugh\n|composer = Jan Paul Moorhead\n|series = ''[[The Riftwar Cycle|Riftwar]]''\n|released = June 22, 1993\n|genre = [[Role-playing game|Role-playing]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[MS-DOS]]\n}}\n\n'''''Betrayal at Krondor''''' is an [[MS-DOS]]-based [[role-playing video game]] developed by [[Dynamix]] and released by [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra On-Line]] in the summer of [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]. ''Betrayal at Krondor'' takes place largely in [[Midkemia]], the [[fantasy literature|fantasy world]] developed by [[Raymond E. Feist]] in his ''[[Riftwar]]'' novels. The game is designed to resemble a book, separated into chapters and narrated in the third-person with a quick-save bookmark feature.\n\nAlthough neither the dialog nor narrative were written by Feist himself, the game is considered canon, having been novelized as ''[[Krondor: The Betrayal]]'' five years later. Events in the game were also written into the ''[[Riftwar]]'' novels.\n\nPyroTechnix completed a sequel, ''[[Return to Krondor]]'', which was released by Sierra in 1998. Its protracted development experienced [[development hell|considerable delay]], and the finished product was not nearly as warmly received as ''Betrayal''.\n\n[[GOG.com]] released an [[Emulator|emulated]] version of ''Betrayal at Krondor'' for [[Microsoft Windows]] in 2010.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - main interface.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The main interface of ''Betrayal at Krondor''. The party is travelling east along a road.]]\nGameplay occurs mainly from a first-person perspective while traveling the overworld, dungeons, and caves, but switches to a third-person view during combat. The user interface is mouse-driven, with keyboard hotkeys for each action.\n\nThe game has two possible views, the 3D first-person view and the 2D top-down map view, where the player is represented with a triangular marker. The overworld is completely mapped, but other locations are [[automap|automatically mapped]] in the top-down view as the player explores them. The player can also view the full map of [[Midkemia]] and see their location.\n\nEach chapter's main plot usually takes place completely within one or two regions of the game world. However, the player is given enormous freedom to explore the world however they wish, with ample opportunity to perform optional sub-quests and enhance their characters' abilities, gain cash, upgrade weapons and armor, and so on. Only certain locations are accessible in each chapter, though the player is free to explore anywhere within those boundaries as well as take their time performing quests. While traveling, the party camps in the wilderness to rest and recover lost health and stamina, provided that there are no enemies in the vicinity.\n\n===Moredhel wordlock chests===\nOne of the game's unique features are the large assortment of [[Moredhel]] wordlock chests, hidden throughout the land. These chests have [[combination lock]]s with letters on each dial, and a [[riddle]] written upon them whose answer opens the chest. Wordlock chests can hold valuable items and equipment, as well as quest items essential to completing the game. If no member of the player's party can read Moredhel, the writing on the chest will appear untranslated, although it can still be opened by a [[brute-force attack|brute force]] method of systematically cycling through each tumbler. The Moredhel alphabet is a character substitution of the A-Z alphabet. Gorath, a Moredhel, can read it, and casting the Union spell allows Patrus to do so for short periods of time. Wordlock chests containing essential quest items are relatively easy to find, either located near roads or their locations being disclosed through interaction with NPCs. However, \"bonus\" wordlock chests are typically hidden in areas where the player is not likely to travel unless they are assiduously searching for treasure.\n\n===Plot and dialogue===\nThe storyline is advanced primarily through literary cutscenes. Each chapter begins and ends with a cutscene, consisting of text, dialogue, and animations. The player meets various NPCs during their travels. Dialogue is text-based and some NPCs have their own pictures as well. Conversation is [[tree (data structure)|tree]]-based: in some cases, the player can choose between various dialogue keywords. This is used to get information, training, and items, sometimes for a price.\n\n===RPG system and player character development===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - character sheet.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Character sheet. Two skills - melee and crossbow accuracy - are emphasized, as indicated by the red pommels of the swords.]]\nThere are two or three characters in the adventuring party at any time. While the player meets various non-human characters during the game (including dwarves, elves, goblins, and dragons), five of the six player characters are human. The exception being Gorath, a dark elf. There are two classes of characters: fighters (Locklear, James, and Gorath) and magicians (Pug, Owyn, and Patrus). Fighters use [[sword]]s and [[crossbow]]s, while magicians use a [[Magic wand|staff]]. The only long-range attacks magicians are capable of are magic spells.\n\nThe character system is unique. The main character attributes are health, stamina, speed, and strength. Speed determines how many combat grid squares the character can move. Strength influences the amount of damage the character inflicts in [[m\u00eal\u00e9e]] combat. Spell-casting, swinging one's weapon, and combat damage first use up stamina. Once stamina is depleted, you begin to eat into health. Once it decreases, the character's skills (such as the crucial trait of weapon accuracy), as well as their movement speed, are adversely impacted.\n\nIn addition to attributes, each character has a set of skills expressed as percentages. Skills can be emphasized, causing them to improve faster, while de-emphasized skills improve slower. Unlike many other role-playing games, skills are improved by using them rather than through a leveling up system. For example, fixing weapons will improve the weaponcraft skill, which in turn will make the character more effective at fixing weapons in the future. Skills include defense, crossbow accuracy, m\u00eal\u00e9e weapon accuracy, spell-casting accuracy, enemy assessment, weapon and armor repair, barding, haggling, [[lockpicking]], scouting for ambushes, and stealth. Some NPCs offer training in skills and items can increase skills permanently or temporarily.\n\nCharacters can acquire various status effects that affect their health or skills. Characters whose health drops to zero in combat are knocked out and acquire \"near death\" status, making them ineffective in combat, and their health recovery rate drops virtually to nil. If the health of the entire party drops to zero, the game will end. Improved healing rate is handled as a status effect as well, as are poisoning, drunkenness, sickness (from eating spoiled rations), and plague, which is an extremely serious condition that can reduce the party to moribund husks incapable of any productive action.\n\n===Magic===\n<!--[[File:Betrayal at Krondor-Magic.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Combat spell-casting menu. Groups of spells are chosen through the buttons, spells itself through the symbols that appear within the pattern. For variable-strength spells, the desired magnitude is chosen by clicking the rim of the pattern.]]-->\nSpells are organized into six groups, grouped by magic symbol. Four groups of spells are combat spells and two groups are non-combat spells.\n\nSpells first drain the caster's stamina and then health. Some spells have variable strength; the player can choose how much energy the spell consumes. Some combat spells also require that the target being within line of sight of the caster.\n\nSpells are learned from scrolls that are found in caches or on enemies and can be bought from shops or NPCs throughout the world.\n\n===Items and inventory===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - inventory.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Inventory screen.]]\nThe game features a wide variety of items, including equipment, food, treasure, and magical artifacts. Each item also has detailed background information available by right-clicking it.\n\nThe inventory management allows transferring items between the party characters. In the case of stacks of multiple items, there's also an option to distribute them evenly within the party. The game also manages money and keys independently.\n\nEach weapon and type of armor has modifiers affecting its combat effectiveness, such as accuracy, damage, blessing, and racial modifiers. After combat, most weapons and armor must be kept in shape with a whetstone or armorer's hammer respectively. There are also items that enhance weapons and armor, such as the poisonous silverthorn or fiery [[naphtha]].\n\nPlayer characters must carry and eat rations every day or their health starts dropping. Rations are sold in taverns and can be found on enemies and in caches. Rations can also be poisoned or spoiled and will sicken characters if they eat it, adversely affecting their health, although careful inspection of all packages of questionable provenance will avoid this possibility.\n\n===Combat===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor.jpg|left|thumb|300px|A battle scene. Gorath, marked with a green square on the grid, is having his turn; hovering mouse over the target marks it with a yellow square, and shows attack damage estimate on the bottom of the screen.]]\nCombat is turn-based and takes place on a grid, similar to [[tactical role-playing game]]s. The characters can move to a different location on the grid and if they can reach an enemy, can attack in the same move. There are two options for attacking: a thrust and a swing. The thrust is the default attack used when moving to attack an enemy. The swing often does more damage but is less accurate and uses up one point of health/stamina. Fighters can use crossbows and magicians can cast spells, but only if there are no enemy units in adjacent squares. The player can also rest, which regains health and stamina, defend against enemy m\u00eal\u00e9e attacks, or assess an enemy's capabilities.\n\nInjured enemies may try to flee from combat, and will escape entirely and permanently from the player's grasp,  unless they are killed or otherwise prevented them from reaching the upper edge of the battlefield. Defeated enemies remain on the ground after a battle, allowing the player to loot their remains. Salvaged items of little use to the party may be sold at shops in order to boost cash reserves.\n\nThe combat interface is also used to solve magical traps. Traps involve various types of hazards, such as fireball blasters and laser crystals, and the player either has to disable them using the objects provided or otherwise navigate through the trap and reach the top of the combat field.\n\nAlthough the game uses a [[GUI]], many actions can be performed using keys as well. There is a [[glitch]] (or intended hidden feature) that allows the player to make certain combinations of two moves in a single turn\u2014one using the mouse and another using the keyboard\u2014or rest twice by pressing 'R' before the turn begins and holding it through the turn. Computer opponents also seem to use this in some instances (like moving and defending in the same turn).\n\nAnother type of character-environment interaction, that could be considered a trap or a bonus, are the graveyards scattered around the landscape. The player is able to read the inscriptions on the gravestones (usually in the form of a short poetic eulogy), and then decide to dig up the grave (if someone has a shovel). Some graves reveal items and/or money, while others summon a ghost (in some cases, multiple ghosts), which must be fought using the standard combat interface.\n\n===Temples, stores and inns===\nTemples offer a variety of services including healing and blessing equipment. They also sell a relatively expensive [[teleportation]] service; the player is able to teleport between any temples they have already visited, with the price based on the distance traveled. This operates on the principle that a person visiting a new temple will memorize a unique pattern upon the wall, and by recalling this pattern at a different temple, be transported to the first temple with the aid of a priest.\n\nStores buy and sell various kinds of items; some also repair equipment. Inns and taverns allow characters to buy food and alcohol, gain information on local happenings, gamble (in some inns), talk to some NPCs, earn money by playing the lute, and sleep, which allows full healing of wounds and fatigue, whereas resting in the wilderness only restores 80% of health and stamina.\n\n==Characters==\n===Main characters===\n; Seigneur Locklear\n: (Chapters 1, 5, 7) Locklear is the youngest son of the Baron of Land's End, a Seigneur in Prince Arutha's court, and a skilled swordsman decorated for his service at Armengar and Sethanon during the Great Rising (''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]''). Locklear recently entered the service of a Kingdom garrison in Yabon to investigate reports of moredhel activity, where he rescued Gorath of the Ardanien from an assassin.\n\n; Squire Owyn Beleforte\n: (Chapters 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9) Owyn is a nineteen-year-old magician and the youngest son of the Count of Tiburn. Uninterested in politics, Owyn instead idolizes the magician Pug. A resourceful and crafty boy, Owyn used part of his father's wealth to travel and study magic in secret. His father eventually discovered what he was doing and, due to the political embarrassment Owyn causes him, has given him a great deal of freedom, hoping that he will eventually settle down and become suitable for a political marriage. Owyn was traveling home from visiting his aunt in Yabon when he met Locklear and Gorath. Not eager to return to the boredom of life at home, Owyn hitches his fate to theirs.\n\n; Gorath of the Ardanien\n: (Chapters 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9) A hero of the Riftwar, Gorath was chieftain of Clan Ardanien and Delekhan's chief rival to the throne of Sar-Sargoth. Gorath believes Delekhan's plan to invade the Kingdom to be madness and betrays the moredhel to warn Prince Arutha, as it the only way to save his people from another disastrous war. There is also another reason for his exile: he has broken from the Dark Path and is \"Returning\" to the eledhel in Elvandar, assuming he is not killed by his brethren first.\n\n; Seigneur James\n: (Chapters 2, 3, 5, 7) Once known as Jimmy the Hand, James is a legend among the Mockers and the son of the Upright Man, though he is unaware of his parentage. After foiling a Nighthawk attempt to assassinate Prince Arutha (''[[Silverthorn (novel)|Silverthorn]]''), James was forced to give up his life as a thief and became a squire in Arutha's court, where he became best friends with Locklear. James eventually rose to the rank of Seigneur, becoming one of Arutha's most trusted and loyal servants but still wanders the Thieves' Highway, often on business for the Crown.\n\n; Patrus\n: (Chapters 5, 7) Patrus is the court magician and magical adviser to Baron Gabot in Northwarden and one of Owyn's early magical tutors. Despite his old age, he is a spry and capable magician, whose knowledge of the Union spell allows him to temporarily read moredhel.\n\n; Duke [[Pug (fictional character)|Pug conDoin]]\n: (Chapters 8, 9) As an orphan growing up in [[Crydee]], Pug was apprenticed to Kulgan the magician but showed little magical ability until he was captured by the [[Tsurani]] during the Riftwar (''[[Magician (Feist novel)|Magician: Apprentice]]''). Seeing potential in the boy, Tsurani Great Ones trained him in the magic of the Greater Path, previously nonexistent in Midkemia. When he returned, Pug helped the sorcerer [[Macros the Black]] end the Riftwar and was adopted into the royal family and given land to start his academy of magic at Stardock (''[[Magician (Feist novel)|Magician: Master]]''). Pug is considered the most powerful magician in Midkemia, having inherited much of Macros' power in addition to his Tsurani training. He is married to Katala, whom he met in Kelewan, and has two children: a biological son William and an adopted daughter Gamina, who has telepathic powers.\n\n===Allies===\n; Prince [[Arutha ConDoin|Arutha conDoin]]\n: Prince Arutha of Krondor is ruler of the Western Realm, younger brother of [[Lyam ConDoin|King Lyam]], and half-brother of Duke Martin of Crydee. Arutha proved himself one of the Kingdom's best field commanders defending Crydee during the Riftwar and became prince after the unexpected deaths of King Rodric, Prince Erland, and his father Duke Borric. He is a well-loved and capable ruler, albeit a reluctant one.\n\n; Cullich\n: Gorath's estranged wife Cullich is a moredhel witch who helped him escape from the Northlands. Cullich thinks Gorath's willingness to surrender his position as clan leader is a sign of weakness but she doesn't trust Delekhan and will help Gorath if she can.\n\n; Baron Gabot\n: Baron Gabot is commander of Northwarden, which guards one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Previously Huntmaster of Carse, Gabot was old acquaintances with Duke Martin, who recommended him to the position after Baron Rossol died. Like Martin's father Duke Borric, Gabot saw the benefit of having a magician in his service and appointed Patrus his magical adviser.\n\n; Liallan\n: As a powerful moredhel clan leader and Delekhan's consort, Liallan openly supports him though she believes his plan is doomed to fail. She has her eye on the throne of Sar-Sargoth for herself and secretly aids many of Delekhan's enemies, including engineering Gorath's escape from the Northlands. Should Delekhan and his son Moraeulf die during their invasion, it would leave her in a prime position to take over the leadership of the moredhel.\n\n; Duke Martin conDoin\n: Once known as Martin Longbow, Duke Martin of Crydee is the elder half-brother of King Lyam and Prince Arutha. The illegitimate son of Duke Borric, he was raised and trained by the elves in Elvandar before becoming Huntmaster and later Duke upon the death of his father. One of the best archers in Midkemia, Martin dislikes court life and often roams the forests with his longbow in hand.\n\n; The Oracle of Aal\n: The Aal are among the oldest races in the universe and one of the few to survive the Chaos Wars between the Valheru and the gods. The Oracle, the last of its dying race, agreed to help Pug and Tomas during the Great Rising in exchange for salvation. After the battle of Sethanon, Pug brought the Oracle to Sethanon and placed it in the body of the dragon Ryath, whose mind was drained by a Dreadlord (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). The Oracle of Aal now watches over the Lifestone and will send warning to Pug and a secret garrison near Sethanon if it is disturbed.\n\n; Squire Phillip\n: Though he appears to be a young noble about Owyn's age, Phillip is actually thirty-seven, a captain in the Kingdom Army, and a courier for the secret garrison near Sethanon. Owyn met him at a party in Yabon prior to the start of the game and meets him again throughout his travels.\n\n; Tomas\n: Prince Consort to Queen Aglaranna and Warleader of Elvandar, Tomas grew up in Crydee with his best friend Pug. During the Riftwar, Tomas discovered the dying dragon Rhuagh, who gave him an ancient suit of armor (''Magician: Apprentice''). The armor transformed Tomas into a blend of human and Valheru and gave him the memories and abilities of Ashen-Shugar, the Valheru to whom it once belonged. After marrying Aglaranna, Tomas considers Elvandar under his protection and only leaves in the most extreme of circumstances.\n\n===Villains===\n; Delekhan\n: Delekhan is the leader of the Moredhel Nations of the North. One of the Murmandamus' field generals during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''), Delekhan believes Murmandamus still lives, imprisoned by Prince Arutha at Sethanon. He has unified his people with the help of magicians known only as \"the Six\" (later revealed to be Tsurani Great Ones) in order to invade the [[Kingdom of the Isles]], free Murmandamus, and finish what was started a decade before.\n\n; Makala\n: Makala is a Great One, a magician from the Tsurani homeworld of [[Kelewan]], who is visiting Prince Arutha's court ostensibly as a representative of the Emperor of Tsuranuanni. Believing that Pug hid a weapon of tremendous power which could be used against the Tsurani, Makala set out to investigate what really happened at the battle of Sethanon. He manipulates Delekhan and the moredhel, using their attack as a diversion so that he can enter Sethanon unhindered.\n\n; Narab and Nago\n: The brothers Narab and Nago are magicians who serve Delekhan. Nago has infiltrated the Kingdom and coordinates moredhel spies from a secret location near Sarth. Narab has fallen out of favor with Delekhan, and seeking to regain his position in Delekhan's inner circle, captures Owyn and Gorath for him. However, Delekhan is displeased with what he has done so Narab turns on his former master and helps Owyn and Gorath escape. He then plans on becoming leader of the moredhel himself.\n\n; Navon du Sandau\n: To most he is simply a charismatic young merchant, but Navon is actually Neville Corvalis, the half-brother of Owyn's cousin Ugyne. When Ugyne's father Count Corvalis found out that Neville was his wife's illegitimate son, he arranged to have Neville killed in a wine cellar collapse. Though he was believed dead, Neville's body was never found. He was found by Nighthawks who had regrouped in Cavall after their destruction in Krondor by Prince Arutha (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Using a Corvalis family heirloom, a magical spyglass, Neville convinced them he had magical powers and became their leader. He then set about exacting revenge on Count Corvalis, burning down the keep so the caverns underneath could be used as a Nighthawk hideout and courting Ugyne so he could take over her family's fortune.\n\n==Locations==\n\n===Midkemia===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Betrayal at Krondor-MidkemiaMap.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Midkemia, the Kingdom of the Isles, the Northlands, and Elvandar \u2013 as shown on the paper map included with Betrayal at Krondor|{{Deletable image-caption|1=Sunday, 11 October 2009|date=May 2012}}]] -->\n\n; Cavall Keep\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Cavall Keep is a small eastern farming town in the Kenting Hills ruled by Owyn's uncle, Count Geoffrey Corvalis. The keep burned down mysteriously three years ago, preventing access to the caverns underneath, which run south to the waterfall known as Cavall Run.\n\n; [[Elvandar]]\n: (Accessible in Chapter 6) The forest city of Elvandar, home of the eledhel (the light elves), lies far to the northwest of the duchy of Yabon and is ruled by Queen Aglaranna and Prince Consort Tomas. Though isolated and well-protected, the Tsurani attacked Elvandar during the Riftwar and there are still skirmishes with the moredhel on its northern borders.\n\n; Highcastle\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3) The frontier fort town of Highcastle guards Cutter's Gap, one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Overrun by the moredhel during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''), Prince Arutha had the fortifications reinforced in recent years. Highcastle is currently commanded by Baron Baldwin de la Troville and, in his absence, Baron Kevin of Zun.\n\n; Krondor\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Capital of the Western Realm of the Kingdom of the Isles, Krondor is the traditional home of the heir apparent to the throne. It is currently ruled by Prince Arutha and Princess Anita, though the sewers under the city are a maze of tunnels known as the Thieves' Highway and controlled by the Mockers, the thieves' guild of Krondor, and their mysterious leader, the Upright Man.\n\n; LaMut\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The city of LaMut is located in the duchy of Yabon, near the reopened rift to Kelewan. It is ruled by the Earl Kasumi and home to a large Tsurani population that settled there after the Riftwar.\n[[File:BaK Midkemia map.gif|left|thumb|200px|The in-game map of Midkemia]]\n\n; Malac's Cross\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The city of Malac's Cross marks the eastern boundary of the Western Realm and is home to the Abbaye Ishap, an ancient temple currently run by the Abbot Graves. Outside of the city, where the old city once stood, is a statue of a dragon, built as a tribute to Malac, from which the Oracle of Aal can be contacted.\n\n; Northwarden\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 5) The fortress of Northwarden lies on a narrow mountain path overlooking one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Northwarden is currently commanded by Baron Gabot.\n\n; Romney\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Located on the river Rom, the eastern city of Romney is known as the City of Guilds. Although ruled by Duke Romney, control of the city lies with its various merchant guilds, leading to the occasional guild war.\n\n; Sarth\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The town of Sarth is home to an ancient mountaintop fortress which was converted into an abbey and library by the Order of Ishap. The vaults have hundreds of thousands of books, containing a wealth of knowledge about the history and lore of Midkemia, tended to by Brother Anthony and Brother Marc. Beneath the vaults is an abandoned dwarven emerald mine known as the Mac Bourgalan Dok.\n\n; Sar-Isbandia (Armengar)\n: (Accessible in Chapter 4) The fortress city of Sar-Isbandia was built atop miles of naphtha tunnels long ago by the glamredhel (the mad elves) before they were obliterated by the moredhel (the dark elves). Located in the Vale of Isbandia north of the Inclindel Gap, humans from Yabon settled in the city hundreds of years ago, renamed it Armengar and became lifelong enemies of the moredhel. The Armengarians were among Murmandamus' first targets during the Great Rising so Prince Arutha and Guy du Bas-Tyra, the city's Protector, evacuated the city and attempted to destroy Murmandamus' army by incinerating the city (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Recently, moredhel have moved into the ruins and started to rebuild.\n\n; Sar-Sargoth\n: (Accessible in Chapter 4) Twin city of Sar-Isbandia, the fortress city of Sar-Sargoth to the north was also built by the glamredhel and was taken by the moredhel as their capital. The tunnels beneath the city are home to Delekhan's dungeons while the outskirts are lined with pikes bearing the heads of his enemies.\n\n; Sethanon\n: (Surface ruins accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6, underground ruins only accessible in Chapter 9) Once a minor barony in the heart of the Kingdom, Sethanon was poorly defended and completely destroyed during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Coincidentally built above the ancient Valheru ruins containing the Lifestone, King Lyam and Prince Arutha ordered the city abandoned after the Battle of Sethanon, ostensibly as a memorial to those who had died there, and stationed a secret garrison nearby to protect it. Within the ruins beneath the city lies the Lifestone and its guardian, the dragon Ryath, whose mind contains the Oracle of Aal.\n\n; Silden\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The eastern fishing town of Silden is a seaport on the Kingdom Sea. Located on a nearby island off the coast is the temple of Eortis, the dead god of the sea. Known for its shady underworld, someone known only as The Crawler has recently establish himself within the city, disrupting business for both the Mockers in Krondor and the guilds in Romney.\n\n===Timirianya===\n: (Accessible in Chapter 8) The desolate world of Timirianya was destroyed by the Valheru and is currently inhabited by Panath-Tiandn, humanoid serpents akin to [[Pantathians]]. During the Chaos Wars, the gods of Timirianya crystallized magic into solid manna, causing the Valheru to leave when they thought the world's energy was depleted. In order to cast magic on Timirianya, one must use a crystal staff and keep it charged with raw manna.\n\n; The Temple of Karzeen Mauk\n: Located in the north, all that remains of the high temple of the gods of Timirianya are nine pillars, within which the surviving gods have taken refuge. Only Dhatsavan, Lord of Gates, still has enough power left to communicate with visitors.\n\n; The Temple of Dhatsavan (Riftworld Mine)\n: Also known as the Riftworld Mine, the ruins of the temple are buried underground and are currently occupied by Panath-Tiandn. After Makala abducts her, Gamina is imprisoned in a crystal cage within the ruins.\n\n==Plot==\nTen years after ''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]'', Seigneur Locklear is serving at a northern Kingdom garrison when he saves Gorath of the Ardanien from an assassin. Gorath has brought a warning of an invasion planned by Delekhan, leader of the moredhel, so Locklear agrees to take him to see Prince Arutha in Krondor. Injured from numerous attacks, they ask for help from Owyn Beleforte, a young magician from Tiburn. The game begins in their camp north of LaMut.\n\n===Chapter I: Into A Dark Night===\nOwyn is bandaging Gorath's and Locklear's injuries when they are attacked by a moredhel assassin whom Gorath dispatches before the three of them set out south. Surviving multiple assassination attempts, they eventually reach Krondor. Finding the palace gates sabotaged, they enter the palace via the sewers with Seigneur James' help. Upon meeting Prince Arutha, another moredhel assassin sneaks in and attempts to kill Gorath, only to be foiled by Pug.\n\n===Chapter II: Shadow Of The Nighthawks===\nGorath informs Arutha of Delekhan's plans, but Arutha does not trust him because he does not know the location of the attack. Gorath thinks they can find out by intercepting Delekhan's Nighthawk spies in Romney. Arutha arranges for James to escort Gorath to Romney and meet with a group of the king's soldiers investigating recent Nighthawk activity in the east. Arutha will muster his army and await word of where the attack will occur. James, Owyn, and Gorath secretly slip out of the city through the sewers and head east. Arriving at the tavern in Romney, they discover that the king's soldiers have all been murdered.\n\n===Chapter III: The Spyglass And The Spider===\nTwo clues were left behind at the murder scene: an enchanted spyglass and a silver spider. James, Owyn, and Gorath follow the trail of the spyglass and the spider north to Cavall Keep and uncover the leader of the Nighthawks, the merchant Navon du Sandau. After killing him, they enter the Nighthawks' hideout in the caverns beneath Cavall Keep, where they learn that Delekhan plans to attack Northwarden. Realizing that Nighthawks probably infiltrated the fortress, they split up. James heads to Northwarden while Owyn and Gorath head south to warn Arutha. Before they can reach Arutha though, Owyn and Gorath are captured by Narab, one of Delekhan's chieftains.\n\n===Chapter IV: Marked For Death===\nGorath and Owyn are taken to Sar-Sargoth, where Narab presents them to Delekhan. Delekhan, enraged that Narab has ruined his plans, tells him his life is forfeit. Narab turns on Delekhan and, unbeknownst to them, frees Owyn and Gorath. They escape Sar-Sargoth and head south to the Inclindel Gap, where they meet a Kingdom patrol and are taken to Arutha's camp. Learning of the impending attack on Northwarden, Arutha readies his army and sends Owyn and Gorath to Krondor to seek Pug's help in case the moredhel employ magic.\n\n===Chapter V: When Rivers Run Blood===\nJames and Locklear arrive at Northwarden and are sent by Baron Gabot to find his magical adviser Patrus. The three of them help Duke Martin prepare for the attack by poisoning moredhel food supplies, finding the minstrel Tamney, stealing the moredhel battle plans, and killing six moredhel magicians hiding behind Kingdom lines. Returning to Northwarden as the moredhel siege begins, they discover that Nighthawks have murdered Baron Gabot, leaving James in command. The battle goes badly and they are about to be overrun when Arutha arrives with his army in time to drive off the moredhel.\n\n===Chapter VI: Betrayal===\nMakala visits Pug in Krondor, telling him that Gamina is considered an abomination by the Assembly of Magicians and that he has imprisoned her until her fate can be decided. Pug is enraged at Makala's betrayal and vows to find her, blasting the words \"The Book Of Macros\" into the wall. When Katala is unable to find him or their daughter, she discovers his message and informs Owyn and Gorath. Following clues from the libraries at Sarth and the Abbaye Ishap, Owyn and Gorath head west to Elvandar, where Gorath completes his \"Returning\" and pledges his allegiance to Queen Aglaranna and Prince Consort Tomas. Tomas shows them the Book of Macros, a gift from Pug to find him should he leave the message to do so. Recently injured by a poisoned blade in a moredhel skirmish, Tomas asks Owyn and Gorath to go in his stead. Owyn and Gorath read the book, which teleports them into the unknown.\n\n===Chapter VII: The Long Ride===\nIn Northwarden, the moredhel raiding leader is captured and reveals that they plan to use a rift machine in the Dimwood to bypass Arutha's army, enter Sethanon, and free Murmandamus, whom they believe is alive and imprisoned there. Realizing that the attack was a diversion engineered by Makala, Arutha orders his troops to Sethanon and instructs James, Locklear, and Patrus to find and destroy the rift machine. After learning that the machine can be disrupted by a Tsurani device called a Waani, they find the machine and disable it. However, as the rift collapses, it pulls in everything nearby before exploding. James and Locklear grab onto trees but Patrus is sucked into the collapsing rift and is apparently killed. At the same moment, three figures appear in a flash of purple light.\n\n===Chapter VIII: Of Lands Afar===\nOwyn and Gorath are teleported to Timirianya, where Owyn realizes that magic does not work and Pug would be powerless. Owyn and Gorath eventually find Pug, who has figured out that by abducting Gamina and manipulating Delekhan, Makala has lured Pug away from Midkemia and Arutha's army away from Sethanon and is free to enter Sethanon unopposed and seek out the Lifestone. Using the Cup of Rlnn Skrr, Owyn restores Pug's powers and they find Gamina imprisoned in a crystal cage in the underground ruins of the Temple of Dhatsavan. Gorath smashes the cage and, using a special pattern stone Pug has brought, the four of them return to Midkemia.\n\n===Chapter IX: Mad Gods Rage===\nIn a flash of purple light, Pug, Owyn, and Gorath appear before James and Locklear in the Dimwood and tell them to wait for Arutha and let him know that there is no magical threat to his army; Makala will be waiting for Pug at Sethanon. Pug, Owyn, and Gorath travel to the caverns beneath Sethanon and kill the Tsurani Great Ones (\"the Six\") protecting the Lifestone Chamber. Gorath remains behind to protect the Oracle of Aal, which was incapacitated by Makala, while Pug and Owyn confront the magician. Makala believes that Pug was keeping the Lifestone hidden to use as a weapon and wants it destroyed, but Pug refuses because it would release the Valheru souls trapped inside. Engaging Makala in a magical battle, Pug and Owyn eventually kill him.\n\nAfterward, Gorath enters the chamber locked in combat with Delekhan. When Delekhan reaches for the Lifestone, Gorath tries to stop him and they begin to transform as the Valheru within try to escape. Pug and Owyn are forced to kill them both with a blast of magic in order to prevent the Valheru from being released. Returning above ground, Pug creates magical illusions of Murmandamus and Delekhan which are then incinerated by the Oracle of Aal. Having seen their leaders killed, the moredhel retreat, during which Narab kills Delekhan's son Moraeulf, fulfilling his plans for taking over the moredhel. Owyn is left alone with Pug, who reveals that since Owyn now knows about the Lifestone, Pug must ensure that the secret is safe and suggests that Owyn become one of his students at Stardock. Owyn laughs and replies that he's never wanted anything else.\n\n==Development==\nAlthough the game was licensed from Raymond E. Feist, a long-held myth was that the text and the story of the game were actually created by Feist himself. Feist states in his afterword to ''Krondor: The Betrayal'' that he was busy writing ''[[Krondor's Sons#The King's Buccaneer|The King's Buccaneer]]'' during the game's production and that the plot, text, and new characters were created solely by designers [[Neal Hallford]] and John Cutter. Feist did have editorial final say on the game, but most of what Hallford and Cutter created was left intact.\n\n===Technical details===\nThe game runs in 256-color 320x200 [[Video Graphics Array|VGA mode]]. The graphics engine uses [[texture mapping|texture]]d [[3D graphics]] to draw the terrain and uses [[sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] for most of the detailed objects. The engine does not support multilevel terrain as such, but obstacles such as hills and mountains are supported. Most shops, inns, temples, special locations, and large cities are navigated through pictures usable through [[Screen hotspot|hotspots]], while smaller towns have 3D buildings.\n\n[[Non-player character|NPC]] and character art is based on photographs. Environments are a mix of captured images and hand-drawn. In combat and puzzle screens, all characters are animated, except for movement - characters do not appear to move their legs while walking. The game models illuminate to a certain extent: in the overworld, day and night are modeled, and in underground locations, the player needs to use a torch or a light spell to illuminate their surroundings.\n\nThe game runs in [[protected mode]], using [[Borland C++]]'s Ergo [[DOS Protected Mode Interface|DPMI]] / RTM  [[DOS extender]].<ref>String in krondor.exe: \"Borland C++ - Copyright 1991 Borland Intl.\"</ref> It remained quite compatible with [[Microsoft Windows]] up to the 9x series and works very well in [[DOSBox]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dosbox.sourceforge.net/comp_list.php?showID=115&letter=B |title=Betrayal at Krondor DOSBox compatibility report |author=Harekiet |accessdate=2006-11-27 }}</ref> and [[VDMSound]]. A playable version for Mac OS X DOSBox is also available. xBaK is a [[game engine recreation]] which allows ''Betrayal at Krondor'' to be played natively under the [[X Window System]], using the original data files.<ref>[http://xbak.sourceforge.net/ xBaK<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Release history===\nThe following commercial editions of the game have been released:\n\n* [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]: The original 3\u00bd\" floppy disk release.\n* [[1994 in video gaming|1994]]: CD-ROM edition, which includes [[Red Book (audio CD standard)|Red Book]] CD-audio versions of the original game's [[MIDI]] music tracks, a 5-minute video interview with Raymond E. Feist, and a Windows hint program/package.\n* [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]: Re-release of the CD-ROM in Sierra's SierraOriginals budget line.<ref>The files on CD-ROM have 1996 timestamps and inner-ring CD-ROM barcode area has July 1996 date. Copyright date of the package is 1993, the original release year.</ref>\n* [[1997 in video gaming|1997]]: free download on Sierra's website to promote the game ''[[Betrayal in Antara]]'', though this version is no longer available.\n* [[1998 in video gaming|1998]]: CD-ROM edition (but without the CD-audio soundtrack) that came with the hardcover edition of ''Krondor: the Betrayal'', with a PDF manual and video interview with Feist, promotional materials and a trailer for ''[[Return to Krondor]]''.\n* [[2010 in video gaming|2010]]: CD-ROM edition re-released on [[GOG.com]] as a downloadable file.<ref>http://www.gog.com/en/gamecard/betrayal_at_krondor/</ref>\n\nContrary to popular belief, [[Vivendi Universal Games]] has stated that the game is not free to be redistributed by others.<ref name=\"vivendi\">{{cite web | author=Matthews, Matt | title=Liberated Games Forums | publisher=liberatedgames.com | date=September 2004 | url=http://www.liberatedgames.com/forums/index.php?t=msg&th=7&start=0&rid=3 | accessdate=2006-03-03 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004160035/http://www.liberatedgames.com/forums/index.php?t=msg&th=7&start=0&rid=3 | archivedate=2008-10-04 }}</ref>\n\n===''Krondor: The Betrayal''===\nFeist later wrote ''[[Krondor: The Betrayal]]'', a novelization of the game and the first in a series of new Midkemia books called ''[[Raymond E. Feist#The Riftwar Legacy|The Riftwar Legacy]]''. Feist credited Hallford and Cutter as co-authors of the original story for ''Krondor: the Betrayal'', and dedicated the book to both of them.\n\nThe game and book are set approximately halfway between ''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]'' and ''[[Prince of the Blood (novel)|Prince of the Blood]]''. There are minor differences, such as Owyn's last name being Belefote rather than Beleforte and the towns of Tanneurs and Eggley are changed to Tannerus and Eggly, but the novel largely covers the main plot of the game accurately and ignores most of the sidequests.\n\nThe game first introduced Lysle Rigger, Jimmy the Hand's long lost twin brother as well as Kat and Abbot Graves, whose granddaughter was Katherine \"Kitty\" Graves. Both Lysle Rigger and Kitty Graves would play significant roles in Feist's [[Raymond E. Feist#The Serpentwar Saga|Serpentwar]] novels.\n\n==Reception==\nSales of the original 3\u00bd\" floppy disk release were slow, leading Sierra to sell the ''Riftwar'' rights back to Raymond Feist, but the game became a hit when it was re-released on CD-ROM.<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=Antara|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=15 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=March 1996|pages=50\u201351}}</ref>\n\n''[[Pelit]]'' gave ''Betrayal at Krondor'' a 94% score, calling the game citing \"the wonderful game system, lack of bugs, and the book-like atmosphere\" and said \"Krondor is as big a revolution in turn-based role-playing games as the ''[[Ultima Underworld|Underworld]]''s were in 3D role-playing games.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Niko |last=Nirvi |author2=Ossi M\u00e4ntylahti |title=Betrayal at Krondor |url=http://www.pelit.fi/index.php?id=60360 |work=[[Pelit]] |publisher=Sanoma Magazines |date=May 1993 |accessdate=2007-01-03 |issn=1235-1199 |language=Finnish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215140510/http://www.pelit.fi/index.php?id=60360 |archivedate=2007-12-15 }}</ref> ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' in October 1993 called ''Krondor'' \"a fantasy role-playing game unlike any other ... a new high-watermark in RPG design\". While noting that the graphics \"are not going to knock players out of their chairs\", the magazine praised combat as \"the best I've seen in a fantasy CRPG\". It concluded that the game was \"a rare gem ... and has set new standards for others to follow. For once, a game actually lives up to, even exceeds, its advance billing\".<ref name=\"kee199310\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=111 | title=My, But You're A Feisty One! | work=Computer Gaming World | date=October 1993 | accessdate=25 March 2016 | author=Kee, Jay | pages=16}}</ref> A less enthusiastic review by [[Sandy Petersen]] appeared in November 1993 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' magazine #199 in the \"Eye of the Monitor\" column, in which he gave the game two stars out of five. Though Petersen praised the graphics for being \"well-rendered\" at times and for its \"rather entertaining plot\", he chastised the gameplay for being slow and for subjecting the player to \"dull maintenance activities\", such as armor polishing, as well as quests that he found frustratingly hard to understand how to complete.<ref name=\"Dragon199\">{{cite journal\n | title=Eye of the Monitor\n | author=Petersen, Sandy\n | journal=Dragon | issue=199 | date=November 1993\n | pages=56\u201364\n | authorlink=Sandy Petersen}}</ref> Quandary gave it a 4.5/5 in its 1996 review, calling it \"no ordinary role-playing game\" with its \"complex\" immersive environment, traps, and riddles replacing \"the usual pits and levers and rolling rocks that are more common in role-playing dungeons.\"  They also called the strategic turn-based combat \"very satisfying\" though \"it takes a little getting used to.\"{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n''Betrayal at Krondor'' was named 1993's best role-playing game and overall \"Game of the Year\" by ''[[Computer Games Magazine|Computer Games Strategy Plus]]''.<ref name=cgm1993awards>{{cite journal | author=Bauman, Steve | journal=[[Computer Games Magazine]] | title=A Decade of Gaming; Award Winners of 1993 |date=November 2000 | issue=120 | pages=58 }}</ref> In June 1994 ''Betrayal at Krondor'' won ''Computer Gaming World''{{'}}s Role-Playing Game of the Year award. The editors wrote that it \"is the quintessential example of how a computer game should be built from a fantasy novel\", stating that they thought it took the most creative risks while readers liked \"its play value and non-linear story\".<ref name=\"cgw199406\">{{Cite magazine\n |last=\n |first=\n |author=\n |last2=\n |first2=\n |date=June 1994\n |title=Announcing The New Premier Awards\n |department=\n |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=118 \n |magazine=Computer Gaming World\n |pages=51\u201358\n |type=\n}}</ref> The magazine ranked ''Krondor'' #43 on their list of the 150 best games of all time in the magazine's November 1996 Anniversary Edition.<ref name=\"cgw199611best\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=150 Best Games of All Time | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=25 March 2016 | pages=64\u201380}}</ref> The magazine added the game to its Hall of Fame in 2001, saying that ''Krondor'' was the \"first role-playing game to offer a 3D environment and...one of the first games to use digitized images effectively in the context of a role-playing game.\"<ref>\n{{cite web | title=CGW's Hall of Fame | work=1UP | author=staff | date=March 23, 2005 | url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3139081 | accessdate=2010-03-02 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522124000/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3139081 | archive-date=May 22, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> In 1994, ''[[PC Gamer US]]'' named ''Betrayal at Krondor'' as the 31st best computer game ever. The editors hailed it as \"a pivotal title in the evolution of role-playing games\", praising its \"interactive plot and characters that stir the emotions of the player.\"<ref name=pcgamerustop40>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | title=''PC Gamer'' Top 40: The Best Games of All Time |date=August 1994 | issue=3 | pages=32\u201342 }}</ref> The magazine later included it on its 1997 \"The Best 50 Games of All-Time\" list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=PC Gamer (US)|date=May 1997}}</ref> In 1998, ''PC Gamer US'' declared it the 44th-best computer game ever released, and the editors called it \"a classic that will last through the ages.\"<ref name=pcgtop50>{{cite journal | author=The ''PC Gamer'' Editors | title=The 50 Best Games Ever | date=October 1998 | volume=5 | number=10 | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | pages=86, 87, 89, 90, 92, 98, 101, 102, 109, 110, 113, 114, 117, 118, 125, 126, 129, 130 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Betrayal in Antara]]'', a spiritual successor developed by Sierra\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/betrayal-at-krondor}}\n* [http://mikesrpgcenter.com/krondor/index.html ''Betrayal at Krondor''] at Mike's RPG Center\n* [http://sourceforge.net/projects/xbak XBAK project], native play under X Window using original files\n\n{{The Riftwar Cycle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Betrayal At Krondor}}\n[[Category:1993 video games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Raymond E. Feist]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Sierra Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games based on novels]]\n[[Category:Games commercially released with DOSBox]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title = Betrayal at Krondor\n|image = Betrayal at Krondor6.jpg\n|developer = [[Dynamix]]\n|publisher = [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra On-Line]]\n|director = John Cutter\n|designer = John Cutter<br>[[Neal Hallford]]\n|programmer = Nels Bruckner\n|artist = Michael McHugh\n|composer = Jan Paul Moorhead\n|series = ''[[The Riftwar Cycle|Riftwar]]''\n|released = June 22, 1993\n|genre = [[Role-playing game|Role-playing]]\n|modes = [[Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[MS-DOS]]\n}}\n\n'''''Betrayal at Krondor''''' is an [[MS-DOS]]-based [[role-playing video game]] developed by [[Dynamix]] and released by [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra On-Line]] in the summer of [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]. ''Betrayal at Krondor'' takes place largely in [[Midkemia]], the [[fantasy literature|fantasy world]] developed by [[Raymond E. Feist]] in his ''[[Riftwar]]'' novels. The game is designed to resemble a book, separated into chapters and narrated in the third-person with a quick-save bookmark feature.\n\nAlthough neither the dialog nor narrative were written by Feist himself, the game is considered canon, having been novelized as ''[[Krondor: The Betrayal]]'' five years later. Events in the game were also written into the ''[[Riftwar]]'' novels.\n\nPyroTechnix completed a sequel, ''[[Return to Krondor]]'', which was released by Sierra in 1998. Its protracted development experienced [[development hell|considerable delay]], and the finished product was not nearly as warmly received as ''Betrayal''.\n\n[[GOG.com]] released an [[Emulator|emulated]] version of ''Betrayal at Krondor'' for [[Microsoft Windows]] in 2010.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - main interface.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The main interface of ''Betrayal at Krondor''. The party is travelling east along a road.]]\nGameplay occurs mainly from a first-person perspective while traveling the overworld, dungeons, and caves, but switches to a third-person view during combat. The user interface is mouse-driven, with keyboard hotkeys for each action.\n\nThe game has two possible views, the 3D first-person view and the 2D top-down map view, where the player is represented with a triangular marker. The overworld is completely mapped, but other locations are [[automap|automatically mapped]] in the top-down view as the player explores them. The player can also view the full map of [[Midkemia]] and see their location.\n\nEach chapter's main plot usually takes place completely within one or two regions of the game world. However, the player is given enormous freedom to explore the world however they wish, with ample opportunity to perform optional sub-quests and enhance their characters' abilities, gain cash, upgrade weapons and armor, and so on. Only certain locations are accessible in each chapter, though the player is free to explore anywhere within those boundaries as well as take their time performing quests. While traveling, the party camps in the wilderness to rest and recover lost health and stamina, provided that there are no enemies in the vicinity.\n\n===Moredhel wordlock chests===\nOne of the game's unique features are the large assortment of [[Moredhel]] wordlock chests, hidden throughout the land. These chests have [[combination lock]]s with letters on each dial, and a [[riddle]] written upon them whose answer opens the chest. Wordlock chests can hold valuable items and equipment, as well as quest items essential to completing the game. If no member of the player's party can read Moredhel, the writing on the chest will appear untranslated, although it can still be opened by a [[brute-force attack|brute force]] method of systematically cycling through each tumbler. The Moredhel alphabet is a character substitution of the A-Z alphabet. Gorath, a Moredhel, can read it, and casting the Union spell allows Patrus to do so for short periods of time. Wordlock chests containing essential quest items are relatively easy to find, either located near roads or their locations being disclosed through interaction with NPCs. However, \"bonus\" wordlock chests are typically hidden in areas where the player is not likely to travel unless they are assiduously searching for treasure.\n\n===Plot and dialogue===\nThe storyline is advanced primarily through literary cutscenes. Each chapter begins and ends with a cutscene, consisting of text, dialogue, and animations. The player meets various NPCs during their travels. Dialogue is text-based and some NPCs have their own pictures as well. Conversation is [[tree (data structure)|tree]]-based: in some cases, the player can choose between various dialogue keywords. This is used to get information, training, and items, sometimes for a price.\n\n===RPG system and player character development===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - character sheet.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Character sheet. Two skills - melee and crossbow accuracy - are emphasized, as indicated by the red pommels of the swords.]]\nThere are two or three characters in the adventuring party at any time. While the player meets various non-human characters during the game (including dwarves, elves, goblins, and dragons), five of the six player characters are human. The exception being Gorath, a dark elf. There are two classes of characters: fighters (Locklear, James, and Gorath) and magicians (Pug, Owyn, and Patrus). Fighters use [[sword]]s and [[crossbow]]s, while magicians use a [[Magic wand|staff]]. The only long-range attacks magicians are capable of are magic spells.\n\nThe character system is unique. The main character attributes are health, stamina, speed, and strength. Speed determines how many combat grid squares the character can move. Strength influences the amount of damage the character inflicts in [[m\u00eal\u00e9e]] combat. Spell-casting, swinging one's weapon, and combat damage first use up stamina. Once stamina is depleted, you begin to eat into health. Once it decreases, the character's skills (such as the crucial trait of weapon accuracy), as well as their movement speed, are adversely impacted.\n\nIn addition to attributes, each character has a set of skills expressed as percentages. Skills can be emphasized, causing them to improve faster, while de-emphasized skills improve slower. Unlike many other role-playing games, skills are improved by using them rather than through a leveling up system. For example, fixing weapons will improve the weaponcraft skill, which in turn will make the character more effective at fixing weapons in the future. Skills include defense, crossbow accuracy, m\u00eal\u00e9e weapon accuracy, spell-casting accuracy, enemy assessment, weapon and armor repair, barding, haggling, [[lockpicking]], scouting for ambushes, and stealth. Some NPCs offer training in skills and items can increase skills permanently or temporarily.\n\nCharacters can acquire various status effects that affect their health or skills. Characters whose health drops to zero in combat are knocked out and acquire \"near death\" status, making them ineffective in combat, and their health recovery rate drops virtually to nil. If the health of the entire party drops to zero, the game will end. Improved healing rate is handled as a status effect as well, as are poisoning, drunkenness, sickness (from eating spoiled rations), and plague, which is an extremely serious condition that can reduce the party to moribund husks incapable of any productive action.\n\n===Magic===\n<!--[[File:Betrayal at Krondor-Magic.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Combat spell-casting menu. Groups of spells are chosen through the buttons, spells itself through the symbols that appear within the pattern. For variable-strength spells, the desired magnitude is chosen by clicking the rim of the pattern.]]-->\nSpells are organized into six groups, grouped by magic symbol. Four groups of spells are combat spells and two groups are non-combat spells.\n\nSpells first drain the caster's stamina and then health. Some spells have variable strength; the player can choose how much energy the spell consumes. Some combat spells also require that the target being within line of sight of the caster.\n\nSpells are learned from scrolls that are found in caches or on enemies and can be bought from shops or NPCs throughout the world.\n\n===Items and inventory===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor - inventory.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Inventory screen.]]\nThe game features a wide variety of items, including equipment, food, treasure, and magical artifacts. Each item also has detailed background information available by right-clicking it.\n\nThe inventory management allows transferring items between the party characters. In the case of stacks of multiple items, there's also an option to distribute them evenly within the party. The game also manages money and keys independently.\n\nEach weapon and type of armor has modifiers affecting its combat effectiveness, such as accuracy, damage, blessing, and racial modifiers. After combat, most weapons and armor must be kept in shape with a whetstone or armorer's hammer respectively. There are also items that enhance weapons and armor, such as the poisonous silverthorn or fiery [[naphtha]].\n\nPlayer characters must carry and eat rations every day or their health starts dropping. Rations are sold in taverns and can be found on enemies and in caches. Rations can also be poisoned or spoiled and will sicken characters if they eat it, adversely affecting their health, although careful inspection of all packages of questionable provenance will avoid this possibility.\n\n===Combat===\n[[File:Betrayal at Krondor.jpg|left|thumb|300px|A battle scene. Gorath, marked with a green square on the grid, is having his turn; hovering mouse over the target marks it with a yellow square, and shows attack damage estimate on the bottom of the screen.]]\nCombat is turn-based and takes place on a grid, similar to [[tactical role-playing game]]s. The characters can move to a different location on the grid and if they can reach an enemy, can attack in the same move. There are two options for attacking: a thrust and a swing. The thrust is the default attack used when moving to attack an enemy. The swing often does more damage but is less accurate and uses up one point of health/stamina. Fighters can use crossbows and magicians can cast spells, but only if there are no enemy units in adjacent squares. The player can also rest, which regains health and stamina, defend against enemy m\u00eal\u00e9e attacks, or assess an enemy's capabilities.\n\nInjured enemies may try to flee from combat, and will escape entirely and permanently from the player's grasp,  unless they are killed or otherwise prevented them from reaching the upper edge of the battlefield. Defeated enemies remain on the ground after a battle, allowing the player to loot their remains. Salvaged items of little use to the party may be sold at shops in order to boost cash reserves.\n\nThe combat interface is also used to solve magical traps. Traps involve various types of hazards, such as fireball blasters and laser crystals, and the player either has to disable them using the objects provided or otherwise navigate through the trap and reach the top of the combat field.\n\nAlthough the game uses a [[GUI]], many actions can be performed using keys as well. There is a [[glitch]] (or intended hidden feature) that allows the player to make certain combinations of two moves in a single turn\u2014one using the mouse and another using the keyboard\u2014or rest twice by pressing 'R' before the turn begins and holding it through the turn. Computer opponents also seem to use this in some instances (like moving and defending in the same turn).\n\nAnother type of character-environment interaction, that could be considered a trap or a bonus, are the graveyards scattered around the landscape. The player is able to read the inscriptions on the gravestones (usually in the form of a short poetic eulogy), and then decide to dig up the grave (if someone has a shovel). Some graves reveal items and/or money, while others summon a ghost (in some cases, multiple ghosts), which must be fought using the standard combat interface.\n\n===Temples, stores and inns===\nTemples offer a variety of services including healing and blessing equipment. They also sell a relatively expensive [[teleportation]] service; the player is able to teleport between any temples they have already visited, with the price based on the distance traveled. This operates on the principle that a person visiting a new temple will memorize a unique pattern upon the wall, and by recalling this pattern at a different temple, be transported to the first temple with the aid of a priest.\n\nStores buy and sell various kinds of items; some also repair equipment. Inns and taverns allow characters to buy food and alcohol, gain information on local happenings, gamble (in some inns), talk to some NPCs, earn money by playing the lute, and sleep, which allows full healing of wounds and fatigue, whereas resting in the wilderness only restores 80% of health and stamina.\n\n==Characters==\n===Main characters===\n; Seigneur Locklear\n: (Chapters 1, 5, 7) Locklear is the youngest son of the Baron of Land's End, a Seigneur in Prince Arutha's court, and a skilled swordsman decorated for his service at Armengar and Sethanon during the Great Rising (''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]''). Locklear recently entered the service of a Kingdom garrison in Yabon to investigate reports of moredhel activity, where he rescued Gorath of the Ardanien from an assassin.\n\n; Squire Owyn Beleforte\n: (Chapters 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9) Owyn is a nineteen-year-old magician and the youngest son of the Count of Tiburn. Uninterested in politics, Owyn instead idolizes the magician Pug. A resourceful and crafty boy, Owyn used part of his father's wealth to travel and study magic in secret. His father eventually discovered what he was doing and, due to the political embarrassment Owyn causes him, has given him a great deal of freedom, hoping that he will eventually settle down and become suitable for a political marriage. Owyn was traveling home from visiting his aunt in Yabon when he met Locklear and Gorath. Not eager to return to the boredom of life at home, Owyn hitches his fate to theirs.\n\n; Gorath of the Ardanien\n: (Chapters 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 9) A hero of the Riftwar, Gorath was chieftain of Clan Ardanien and Delekhan's chief rival to the throne of Sar-Sargoth. Gorath believes Delekhan's plan to invade the Kingdom to be madness and betrays the moredhel to warn Prince Arutha, as it the only way to save his people from another disastrous war. There is also another reason for his exile: he has broken from the Dark Path and is \"Returning\" to the eledhel in Elvandar, assuming he is not killed by his brethren first.\n\n; Seigneur James\n: (Chapters 2, 3, 5, 7) Once known as Jimmy the Hand, James is a legend among the Mockers and the son of the Upright Man, though he is unaware of his parentage. After foiling a Nighthawk attempt to assassinate Prince Arutha (''[[Silverthorn (novel)|Silverthorn]]''), James was forced to give up his life as a thief and became a squire in Arutha's court, where he became best friends with Locklear. James eventually rose to the rank of Seigneur, becoming one of Arutha's most trusted and loyal servants but still wanders the Thieves' Highway, often on business for the Crown.\n\n; Patrus\n: (Chapters 5, 7) Patrus is the court magician and magical adviser to Baron Gabot in Northwarden and one of Owyn's early magical tutors. Despite his old age, he is a spry and capable magician, whose knowledge of the Union spell allows him to temporarily read moredhel.\n\n; Duke [[Pug (fictional character)|Pug conDoin]]\n: (Chapters 8, 9) As an orphan growing up in [[Crydee]], Pug was apprenticed to Kulgan the magician but showed little magical ability until he was captured by the [[Tsurani]] during the Riftwar (''[[Magician (Feist novel)|Magician: Apprentice]]''). Seeing potential in the boy, Tsurani Great Ones trained him in the magic of the Greater Path, previously nonexistent in Midkemia. When he returned, Pug helped the sorcerer [[Macros the Black]] end the Riftwar and was adopted into the royal family and given land to start his academy of magic at Stardock (''[[Magician (Feist novel)|Magician: Master]]''). Pug is considered the most powerful magician in Midkemia, having inherited much of Macros' power in addition to his Tsurani training. He is married to Katala, whom he met in Kelewan, and has two children: a biological son William and an adopted daughter Gamina, who has telepathic powers.\n\n===Allies===\n; Prince [[Arutha ConDoin|Arutha conDoin]]\n: Prince Arutha of Krondor is ruler of the Western Realm, younger brother of [[Lyam ConDoin|King Lyam]], and half-brother of Duke Martin of Crydee. Arutha proved himself one of the Kingdom's best field commanders defending Crydee during the Riftwar and became prince after the unexpected deaths of King Rodric, Prince Erland, and his father Duke Borric. He is a well-loved and capable ruler, albeit a reluctant one.\n\n; Cullich\n: Gorath's estranged wife Cullich is a moredhel witch who helped him escape from the Northlands. Cullich thinks Gorath's willingness to surrender his position as clan leader is a sign of weakness but she doesn't trust Delekhan and will help Gorath if she can.\n\n; Baron Gabot\n: Baron Gabot is commander of Northwarden, which guards one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Previously Huntmaster of Carse, Gabot was old acquaintances with Duke Martin, who recommended him to the position after Baron Rossol died. Like Martin's father Duke Borric, Gabot saw the benefit of having a magician in his service and appointed Patrus his magical adviser.\n\n; Liallan\n: As a powerful moredhel clan leader and Delekhan's consort, Liallan openly supports him though she believes his plan is doomed to fail. She has her eye on the throne of Sar-Sargoth for herself and secretly aids many of Delekhan's enemies, including engineering Gorath's escape from the Northlands. Should Delekhan and his son Moraeulf die during their invasion, it would leave her in a prime position to take over the leadership of the moredhel.\n\n; Duke Martin conDoin\n: Once known as Martin Longbow, Duke Martin of Crydee is the elder half-brother of King Lyam and Prince Arutha. The illegitimate son of Duke Borric, he was raised and trained by the elves in Elvandar before becoming Huntmaster and later Duke upon the death of his father. One of the best archers in Midkemia, Martin dislikes court life and often roams the forests with his longbow in hand.\n\n; The Oracle of Aal\n: The Aal are among the oldest races in the universe and one of the few to survive the Chaos Wars between the Valheru and the gods. The Oracle, the last of its dying race, agreed to help Pug and Tomas during the Great Rising in exchange for salvation. After the battle of Sethanon, Pug brought the Oracle to Sethanon and placed it in the body of the dragon Ryath, whose mind was drained by a Dreadlord (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). The Oracle of Aal now watches over the Lifestone and will send warning to Pug and a secret garrison near Sethanon if it is disturbed.\n\n; Squire Phillip\n: Though he appears to be a young noble about Owyn's age, Phillip is actually thirty-seven, a captain in the Kingdom Army, and a courier for the secret garrison near Sethanon. Owyn met him at a party in Yabon prior to the start of the game and meets him again throughout his travels.\n\n; Tomas\n: Prince Consort to Queen Aglaranna and Warleader of Elvandar, Tomas grew up in Crydee with his best friend Pug. During the Riftwar, Tomas discovered the dying dragon Rhuagh, who gave him an ancient suit of armor (''Magician: Apprentice''). The armor transformed Tomas into a blend of human and Valheru and gave him the memories and abilities of Ashen-Shugar, the Valheru to whom it once belonged. After marrying Aglaranna, Tomas considers Elvandar under his protection and only leaves in the most extreme of circumstances.\n\n===Villains===\n; Delekhan\n: Delekhan is the leader of the Moredhel Nations of the North. One of the Murmandamus' field generals during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''), Delekhan believes Murmandamus still lives, imprisoned by Prince Arutha at Sethanon. He has unified his people with the help of magicians known only as \"the Six\" (later revealed to be Tsurani Great Ones) in order to invade the [[Kingdom of the Isles]], free Murmandamus, and finish what was started a decade before.\n\n; Makala\n: Makala is a Great One, a magician from the Tsurani homeworld of [[Kelewan]], who is visiting Prince Arutha's court ostensibly as a representative of the Emperor of Tsuranuanni. Believing that Pug hid a weapon of tremendous power which could be used against the Tsurani, Makala set out to investigate what really happened at the battle of Sethanon. He manipulates Delekhan and the moredhel, using their attack as a diversion so that he can enter Sethanon unhindered.\n\n; Narab and Nago\n: The brothers Narab and Nago are magicians who serve Delekhan. Nago has infiltrated the Kingdom and coordinates moredhel spies from a secret location near Sarth. Narab has fallen out of favor with Delekhan, and seeking to regain his position in Delekhan's inner circle, captures Owyn and Gorath for him. However, Delekhan is displeased with what he has done so Narab turns on his former master and helps Owyn and Gorath escape. He then plans on becoming leader of the moredhel himself.\n\n; Navon du Sandau\n: To most he is simply a charismatic young merchant, but Navon is actually Neville Corvalis, the half-brother of Owyn's cousin Ugyne. When Ugyne's father Count Corvalis found out that Neville was his wife's illegitimate son, he arranged to have Neville killed in a wine cellar collapse. Though he was believed dead, Neville's body was never found. He was found by Nighthawks who had regrouped in Cavall after their destruction in Krondor by Prince Arutha (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Using a Corvalis family heirloom, a magical spyglass, Neville convinced them he had magical powers and became their leader. He then set about exacting revenge on Count Corvalis, burning down the keep so the caverns underneath could be used as a Nighthawk hideout and courting Ugyne so he could take over her family's fortune.\n\n==Locations==\n\n===Midkemia===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Betrayal at Krondor-MidkemiaMap.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Midkemia, the Kingdom of the Isles, the Northlands, and Elvandar \u2013 as shown on the paper map included with Betrayal at Krondor|{{Deletable image-caption|1=Sunday, 11 October 2009|date=May 2012}}]] -->\n\n; Cavall Keep\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Cavall Keep is a small eastern farming town in the Kenting Hills ruled by Owyn's uncle, Count Geoffrey Corvalis. The keep burned down mysteriously three years ago, preventing access to the caverns underneath, which run south to the waterfall known as Cavall Run.\n\n; [[Elvandar]]\n: (Accessible in Chapter 6) The forest city of Elvandar, home of the eledhel (the light elves), lies far to the northwest of the duchy of Yabon and is ruled by Queen Aglaranna and Prince Consort Tomas. Though isolated and well-protected, the Tsurani attacked Elvandar during the Riftwar and there are still skirmishes with the moredhel on its northern borders.\n\n; Highcastle\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3) The frontier fort town of Highcastle guards Cutter's Gap, one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Overrun by the moredhel during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''), Prince Arutha had the fortifications reinforced in recent years. Highcastle is currently commanded by Baron Baldwin de la Troville and, in his absence, Baron Kevin of Zun.\n\n; Krondor\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Capital of the Western Realm of the Kingdom of the Isles, Krondor is the traditional home of the heir apparent to the throne. It is currently ruled by Prince Arutha and Princess Anita, though the sewers under the city are a maze of tunnels known as the Thieves' Highway and controlled by the Mockers, the thieves' guild of Krondor, and their mysterious leader, the Upright Man.\n\n; LaMut\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The city of LaMut is located in the duchy of Yabon, near the reopened rift to Kelewan. It is ruled by the Earl Kasumi and home to a large Tsurani population that settled there after the Riftwar.\n[[File:BaK Midkemia map.gif|left|thumb|200px|The in-game map of Midkemia]]\n\n; Malac's Cross\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The city of Malac's Cross marks the eastern boundary of the Western Realm and is home to the Abbaye Ishap, an ancient temple currently run by the Abbot Graves. Outside of the city, where the old city once stood, is a statue of a dragon, built as a tribute to Malac, from which the Oracle of Aal can be contacted.\n\n; Northwarden\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 5) The fortress of Northwarden lies on a narrow mountain path overlooking one of the four passes between the Kingdom and the Northlands. Northwarden is currently commanded by Baron Gabot.\n\n; Romney\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) Located on the river Rom, the eastern city of Romney is known as the City of Guilds. Although ruled by Duke Romney, control of the city lies with its various merchant guilds, leading to the occasional guild war.\n\n; Sarth\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The town of Sarth is home to an ancient mountaintop fortress which was converted into an abbey and library by the Order of Ishap. The vaults have hundreds of thousands of books, containing a wealth of knowledge about the history and lore of Midkemia, tended to by Brother Anthony and Brother Marc. Beneath the vaults is an abandoned dwarven emerald mine known as the Mac Bourgalan Dok.\n\n; Sar-Isbandia (Armengar)\n: (Accessible in Chapter 4) The fortress city of Sar-Isbandia was built atop miles of naphtha tunnels long ago by the glamredhel (the mad elves) before they were obliterated by the moredhel (the dark elves). Located in the Vale of Isbandia north of the Inclindel Gap, humans from Yabon settled in the city hundreds of years ago, renamed it Armengar and became lifelong enemies of the moredhel. The Armengarians were among Murmandamus' first targets during the Great Rising so Prince Arutha and Guy du Bas-Tyra, the city's Protector, evacuated the city and attempted to destroy Murmandamus' army by incinerating the city (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Recently, moredhel have moved into the ruins and started to rebuild.\n\n; Sar-Sargoth\n: (Accessible in Chapter 4) Twin city of Sar-Isbandia, the fortress city of Sar-Sargoth to the north was also built by the glamredhel and was taken by the moredhel as their capital. The tunnels beneath the city are home to Delekhan's dungeons while the outskirts are lined with pikes bearing the heads of his enemies.\n\n; Sethanon\n: (Surface ruins accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6, underground ruins only accessible in Chapter 9) Once a minor barony in the heart of the Kingdom, Sethanon was poorly defended and completely destroyed during the Great Rising (''A Darkness at Sethanon''). Coincidentally built above the ancient Valheru ruins containing the Lifestone, King Lyam and Prince Arutha ordered the city abandoned after the Battle of Sethanon, ostensibly as a memorial to those who had died there, and stationed a secret garrison nearby to protect it. Within the ruins beneath the city lies the Lifestone and its guardian, the dragon Ryath, whose mind contains the Oracle of Aal.\n\n; Silden\n: (Accessible in Chapters 1, 2, 3, 6) The eastern fishing town of Silden is a seaport on the Kingdom Sea. Located on a nearby island off the coast is the temple of Eortis, the dead god of the sea. Known for its shady underworld, someone known only as The Crawler has recently establish himself within the city, disrupting business for both the Mockers in Krondor and the guilds in Romney.\n\n===Timirianya===\n: (Accessible in Chapter 8) The desolate world of Timirianya was destroyed by the Valheru and is currently inhabited by Panath-Tiandn, humanoid serpents akin to [[Pantathians]]. During the Chaos Wars, the gods of Timirianya crystallized magic into solid manna, causing the Valheru to leave when they thought the world's energy was depleted. In order to cast magic on Timirianya, one must use a crystal staff and keep it charged with raw manna.\n\n; The Temple of Karzeen Mauk\n: Located in the north, all that remains of the high temple of the gods of Timirianya are nine pillars, within which the surviving gods have taken refuge. Only Dhatsavan, Lord of Gates, still has enough power left to communicate with visitors.\n\n; The Temple of Dhatsavan (Riftworld Mine)\n: Also known as the Riftworld Mine, the ruins of the temple are buried underground and are currently occupied by Panath-Tiandn. After Makala abducts her, Gamina is imprisoned in a crystal cage within the ruins.\n\n==Plot==\nTen years after ''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]'', Seigneur Locklear is serving at a northern Kingdom garrison when he saves Gorath of the Ardanien from an assassin. Gorath has brought a warning of an invasion planned by Delekhan, leader of the moredhel, so Locklear agrees to take him to see Prince Arutha in Krondor. Injured from numerous attacks, they ask for help from Owyn Beleforte, a young magician from Tiburn. The game begins in their camp north of LaMut.\n\n===Chapter I: Into A Dark Night===\nOwyn is bandaging Gorath's and Locklear's injuries when they are attacked by a moredhel assassin whom Gorath dispatches before the three of them set out south. Surviving multiple assassination attempts, they eventually reach Krondor. Finding the palace gates sabotaged, they enter the palace via the sewers with Seigneur James' help. Upon meeting Prince Arutha, another moredhel assassin sneaks in and attempts to kill Gorath, only to be foiled by Pug.\n\n===Chapter II: Shadow Of The Nighthawks===\nGorath informs Arutha of Delekhan's plans, but Arutha does not trust him because he does not know the location of the attack. Gorath thinks they can find out by intercepting Delekhan's Nighthawk spies in Romney. Arutha arranges for James to escort Gorath to Romney and meet with a group of the king's soldiers investigating recent Nighthawk activity in the east. Arutha will muster his army and await word of where the attack will occur. James, Owyn, and Gorath secretly slip out of the city through the sewers and head east. Arriving at the tavern in Romney, they discover that the king's soldiers have all been murdered.\n\n===Chapter III: The Spyglass And The Spider===\nTwo clues were left behind at the murder scene: an enchanted spyglass and a silver spider. James, Owyn, and Gorath follow the trail of the spyglass and the spider north to Cavall Keep and uncover the leader of the Nighthawks, the merchant Navon du Sandau. After killing him, they enter the Nighthawks' hideout in the caverns beneath Cavall Keep, where they learn that Delekhan plans to attack Northwarden. Realizing that Nighthawks probably infiltrated the fortress, they split up. James heads to Northwarden while Owyn and Gorath head south to warn Arutha. Before they can reach Arutha though, Owyn and Gorath are captured by Narab, one of Delekhan's chieftains.\n\n===Chapter IV: Marked For Death===\nGorath and Owyn are taken to Sar-Sargoth, where Narab presents them to Delekhan. Delekhan, enraged that Narab has ruined his plans, tells him his life is forfeit. Narab turns on Delekhan and, unbeknownst to them, frees Owyn and Gorath. They escape Sar-Sargoth and head south to the Inclindel Gap, where they meet a Kingdom patrol and are taken to Arutha's camp. Learning of the impending attack on Northwarden, Arutha readies his army and sends Owyn and Gorath to Krondor to seek Pug's help in case the moredhel employ magic.\n\n===Chapter V: When Rivers Run Blood===\nJames and Locklear arrive at Northwarden and are sent by Baron Gabot to find his magical adviser Patrus. The three of them help Duke Martin prepare for the attack by poisoning moredhel food supplies, finding the minstrel Tamney, stealing the moredhel battle plans, and killing six moredhel magicians hiding behind Kingdom lines. Returning to Northwarden as the moredhel siege begins, they discover that Nighthawks have murdered Baron Gabot, leaving James in command. The battle goes badly and they are about to be overrun when Arutha arrives with his army in time to drive off the moredhel.\n\n===Chapter VI: Betrayal===\nMakala visits Pug in Krondor, telling him that Gamina is considered an abomination by the Assembly of Magicians and that he has imprisoned her until her fate can be decided. Pug is enraged at Makala's betrayal and vows to find her, blasting the words \"The Book Of Macros\" into the wall. When Katala is unable to find him or their daughter, she discovers his message and informs Owyn and Gorath. Following clues from the libraries at Sarth and the Abbaye Ishap, Owyn and Gorath head west to Elvandar, where Gorath completes his \"Returning\" and pledges his allegiance to Queen Aglaranna and Prince Consort Tomas. Tomas shows them the Book of Macros, a gift from Pug to find him should he leave the message to do so. Recently injured by a poisoned blade in a moredhel skirmish, Tomas asks Owyn and Gorath to go in his stead. Owyn and Gorath read the book, which teleports them into the unknown.\n\n===Chapter VII: The Long Ride===\nIn Northwarden, the moredhel raiding leader is captured and reveals that they plan to use a rift machine in the Dimwood to bypass Arutha's army, enter Sethanon, and free Murmandamus, whom they believe is alive and imprisoned there. Realizing that the attack was a diversion engineered by Makala, Arutha orders his troops to Sethanon and instructs James, Locklear, and Patrus to find and destroy the rift machine. After learning that the machine can be disrupted by a Tsurani device called a Waani, they find the machine and disable it. However, as the rift collapses, it pulls in everything nearby before exploding. James and Locklear grab onto trees but Patrus is sucked into the collapsing rift and is apparently killed. At the same moment, three figures appear in a flash of purple light.\n\n===Chapter VIII: Of Lands Afar===\nOwyn and Gorath are teleported to Timirianya, where Owyn realizes that magic does not work and Pug would be powerless. Owyn and Gorath eventually find Pug, who has figured out that by abducting Gamina and manipulating Delekhan, Makala has lured Pug away from Midkemia and Arutha's army away from Sethanon and is free to enter Sethanon unopposed and seek out the Lifestone. Using the Cup of Rlnn Skrr, Owyn restores Pug's powers and they find Gamina imprisoned in a crystal cage in the underground ruins of the Temple of Dhatsavan. Gorath smashes the cage and, using a special pattern stone Pug has brought, the four of them return to Midkemia.\n\n===Chapter IX: Mad Gods Rage===\nIn a flash of purple light, Pug, Owyn, and Gorath appear before James and Locklear in the Dimwood and tell them to wait for Arutha and let him know that there is no magical threat to his army; Makala will be waiting for Pug at Sethanon. Pug, Owyn, and Gorath travel to the caverns beneath Sethanon and kill the Tsurani Great Ones (\"the Six\") protecting the Lifestone Chamber. Gorath remains behind to protect the Oracle of Aal, which was incapacitated by Makala, while Pug and Owyn confront the magician. Makala believes that Pug was keeping the Lifestone hidden to use as a weapon and wants it destroyed, but Pug refuses because it would release the Valheru souls trapped inside. Engaging Makala in a magical battle, Pug and Owyn eventually kill him.\n\nAfterward, Gorath enters the chamber locked in combat with Delekhan. When Delekhan reaches for the Lifestone, Gorath tries to stop him and they begin to transform as the Valheru within try to escape. Pug and Owyn are forced to kill them both with a blast of magic in order to prevent the Valheru from being released. Returning above ground, Pug creates magical illusions of Murmandamus and Delekhan which are then incinerated by the Oracle of Aal. Having seen their leaders killed, the moredhel retreat, during which Narab kills Delekhan's son Moraeulf, fulfilling his plans for taking over the moredhel. Owyn is left alone with Pug, who reveals that since Owyn now knows about the Lifestone, Pug must ensure that the secret is safe and suggests that Owyn become one of his students at Stardock. Owyn laughs and replies that he's never wanted anything else.\n\n==Development==\nAlthough the game was licensed from Raymond E. Feist, a long-held myth was that the text and the story of the game were actually created by Feist himself. Feist states in his afterword to ''Krondor: The Betrayal'' that he was busy writing ''[[Krondor's Sons#The King's Buccaneer|The King's Buccaneer]]'' during the game's production and that the plot, text, and new characters were created solely by designers [[Neal Hallford]] and John Cutter. Feist did have editorial final say on the game, but most of what Hallford and Cutter created was left intact.\n\n===Technical details===\nThe game runs in 256-color 320x200 [[Video Graphics Array|VGA mode]]. The graphics engine uses [[texture mapping|texture]]d [[3D graphics]] to draw the terrain and uses [[sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] for most of the detailed objects. The engine does not support multilevel terrain as such, but obstacles such as hills and mountains are supported. Most shops, inns, temples, special locations, and large cities are navigated though pictures usable through [[Screen hotspot|hotspots]], while smaller towns have 3D buildings.\n\n[[Non-player character|NPC]] and character art is based on photographs. Environments are a mix of captured images and hand-drawn. In combat and puzzle screens, all characters are animated, except for movement - characters do not appear to move their legs while walking. The game models illuminate to a certain extent: in the overworld, day and night are modeled, and in underground locations, the player needs to use a torch or a light spell to illuminate their surroundings.\n\nThe game runs in [[protected mode]], using [[Borland C++]]'s Ergo [[DOS Protected Mode Interface|DPMI]] / RTM  [[DOS extender]].<ref>String in krondor.exe: \"Borland C++ - Copyright 1991 Borland Intl.\"</ref> It remained quite compatible with [[Microsoft Windows]] up to the 9x series and works very well in [[DOSBox]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dosbox.sourceforge.net/comp_list.php?showID=115&letter=B |title=Betrayal at Krondor DOSBox compatibility report |author=Harekiet |accessdate=2006-11-27 }}</ref> and [[VDMSound]]. A playable version for Mac OS X DOSBox is also available. xBaK is a [[game engine recreation]] which allows ''Betrayal at Krondor'' to be played natively under the [[X Window System]], using the original data files.<ref>[http://xbak.sourceforge.net/ xBaK<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Release history===\nThe following commercial editions of the game have been released:\n\n* [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]: The original 3\u00bd\" floppy disk release.\n* [[1994 in video gaming|1994]]: CD-ROM edition, which includes [[Red Book (audio CD standard)|Red Book]] CD-audio versions of the original game's [[MIDI]] music tracks, a 5-minute video interview with Raymond E. Feist, and a Windows hint program/package.\n* [[1996 in video gaming|1996]]: Re-release of the CD-ROM in Sierra's SierraOriginals budget line.<ref>The files on CD-ROM have 1996 timestamps and inner-ring CD-ROM barcode area has July 1996 date. Copyright date of the package is 1993, the original release year.</ref>\n* [[1997 in video gaming|1997]]: free download on Sierra's website to promote the game ''[[Betrayal in Antara]]'', though this version is no longer available.\n* [[1998 in video gaming|1998]]: CD-ROM edition (but without the CD-audio soundtrack) that came with the hardcover edition of ''Krondor: the Betrayal'', with a PDF manual and video interview with Feist, promotional materials and a trailer for ''[[Return to Krondor]]''.\n* [[2010 in video gaming|2010]]: CD-ROM edition re-released on [[GOG.com]] as a downloadable file.<ref>http://www.gog.com/en/gamecard/betrayal_at_krondor/</ref>\n\nContrary to popular belief, [[Vivendi Universal Games]] has stated that the game is not free to be redistributed by others.<ref name=\"vivendi\">{{cite web | author=Matthews, Matt | title=Liberated Games Forums | publisher=liberatedgames.com | date=September 2004 | url=http://www.liberatedgames.com/forums/index.php?t=msg&th=7&start=0&rid=3 | accessdate=2006-03-03 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004160035/http://www.liberatedgames.com/forums/index.php?t=msg&th=7&start=0&rid=3 | archivedate=2008-10-04 }}</ref>\n\n===''Krondor: The Betrayal''===\nFeist later wrote ''[[Krondor: The Betrayal]]'', a novelization of the game and the first in a series of new Midkemia books called ''[[Raymond E. Feist#The Riftwar Legacy|The Riftwar Legacy]]''. Feist credited Hallford and Cutter as co-authors of the original story for ''Krondor: the Betrayal'', and dedicated the book to both of them.\n\nThe game and book are set approximately halfway between ''[[A Darkness at Sethanon]]'' and ''[[Prince of the Blood (novel)|Prince of the Blood]]''. There are minor differences, such as Owyn's last name being Belefote rather than Beleforte and the towns of Tanneurs and Eggley are changed to Tannerus and Eggly, but the novel largely covers the main plot of the game accurately and ignores most of the sidequests.\n\nThe game first introduced Lysle Rigger, Jimmy the Hand's long lost twin brother as well as Kat and Abbot Graves, whose granddaughter was Katherine \"Kitty\" Graves. Both Lysle Rigger and Kitty Graves would play significant roles in Feist's [[Raymond E. Feist#The Serpentwar Saga|Serpentwar]] novels.\n\n==Reception==\nSales of the original 3\u00bd\" floppy disk release were slow, leading Sierra to sell the ''Riftwar'' rights back to Raymond Feist, but the game became a hit when it was re-released on CD-ROM.<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=Antara|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=15 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=March 1996|pages=50\u201351}}</ref>\n\n''[[Pelit]]'' gave ''Betrayal at Krondor'' a 94% score, calling the game citing \"the wonderful game system, lack of bugs, and the book-like atmosphere\" and said \"Krondor is as big a revolution in turn-based role-playing games as the ''[[Ultima Underworld|Underworld]]''s were in 3D role-playing games.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Niko |last=Nirvi |author2=Ossi M\u00e4ntylahti |title=Betrayal at Krondor |url=http://www.pelit.fi/index.php?id=60360 |work=[[Pelit]] |publisher=Sanoma Magazines |date=May 1993 |accessdate=2007-01-03 |issn=1235-1199 |language=Finnish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215140510/http://www.pelit.fi/index.php?id=60360 |archivedate=2007-12-15 }}</ref> ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' in October 1993 called ''Krondor'' \"a fantasy role-playing game unlike any other ... a new high-watermark in RPG design\". While noting that the graphics \"are not going to knock players out of their chairs\", the magazine praised combat as \"the best I've seen in a fantasy CRPG\". It concluded that the game was \"a rare gem ... and has set new standards for others to follow. For once, a game actually lives up to, even exceeds, its advance billing\".<ref name=\"kee199310\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1993&pub=2&id=111 | title=My, But You're A Feisty One! | work=Computer Gaming World | date=October 1993 | accessdate=25 March 2016 | author=Kee, Jay | pages=16}}</ref> A less enthusiastic review by [[Sandy Petersen]] appeared in November 1993 in ''[[Dragon (magazine)|Dragon]]'' magazine #199 in the \"Eye of the Monitor\" column, in which he gave the game two stars out of five. Though Petersen praised the graphics for being \"well-rendered\" at times and for its \"rather entertaining plot\", he chastised the gameplay for being slow and for subjecting the player to \"dull maintenance activities\", such as armor polishing, as well as quests that he found frustratingly hard to understand how to complete.<ref name=\"Dragon199\">{{cite journal\n | title=Eye of the Monitor\n | author=Petersen, Sandy\n | journal=Dragon | issue=199 | date=November 1993\n | pages=56\u201364\n | authorlink=Sandy Petersen}}</ref> Quandary gave it a 4.5/5 in its 1996 review, calling it \"no ordinary role-playing game\" with its \"complex\" immersive environment, traps, and riddles replacing \"the usual pits and levers and rolling rocks that are more common in role-playing dungeons.\"  They also called the strategic turn-based combat \"very satisfying\" though \"it takes a little getting used to.\"{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n''Betrayal at Krondor'' was named 1993's best role-playing game and overall \"Game of the Year\" by ''[[Computer Games Magazine|Computer Games Strategy Plus]]''.<ref name=cgm1993awards>{{cite journal | author=Bauman, Steve | journal=[[Computer Games Magazine]] | title=A Decade of Gaming; Award Winners of 1993 |date=November 2000 | issue=120 | pages=58 }}</ref> In June 1994 ''Betrayal at Krondor'' won ''Computer Gaming World''{{'}}s Role-Playing Game of the Year award. The editors wrote that it \"is the quintessential example of how a computer game should be built from a fantasy novel\", stating that they thought it took the most creative risks while readers liked \"its play value and non-linear story\".<ref name=\"cgw199406\">{{Cite magazine\n |last=\n |first=\n |author=\n |last2=\n |first2=\n |date=June 1994\n |title=Announcing The New Premier Awards\n |department=\n |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=118 \n |magazine=Computer Gaming World\n |pages=51\u201358\n |type=\n}}</ref> The magazine ranked ''Krondor'' #43 on their list of the 150 best games of all time in the magazine's November 1996 Anniversary Edition.<ref name=\"cgw199611best\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1996&pub=2&id=148 | title=150 Best Games of All Time | work=Computer Gaming World | date=November 1996 | accessdate=25 March 2016 | pages=64\u201380}}</ref> The magazine added the game to its Hall of Fame in 2001, saying that ''Krondor'' was the \"first role-playing game to offer a 3D environment and...one of the first games to use digitized images effectively in the context of a role-playing game.\"<ref>\n{{cite web | title=CGW's Hall of Fame | work=1UP | author=staff | date=March 23, 2005 | url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3139081 | accessdate=2010-03-02 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522124000/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3139081 | archive-date=May 22, 2011 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}\n</ref> In 1994, ''[[PC Gamer US]]'' named ''Betrayal at Krondor'' as the 31st best computer game ever. The editors hailed it as \"a pivotal title in the evolution of role-playing games\", praising its \"interactive plot and characters that stir the emotions of the player.\"<ref name=pcgamerustop40>{{cite journal | author=Staff | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | title=''PC Gamer'' Top 40: The Best Games of All Time |date=August 1994 | issue=3 | pages=32\u201342 }}</ref> The magazine later included it on its 1997 \"The Best 50 Games of All-Time\" list.<ref>{{cite journal|title=PC Gamer (US)|date=May 1997}}</ref> In 1998, ''PC Gamer US'' declared it the 44th-best computer game ever released, and the editors called it \"a classic that will last through the ages.\"<ref name=pcgtop50>{{cite journal | author=The ''PC Gamer'' Editors | title=The 50 Best Games Ever | date=October 1998 | volume=5 | number=10 | journal=[[PC Gamer US]] | pages=86, 87, 89, 90, 92, 98, 101, 102, 109, 110, 113, 114, 117, 118, 125, 126, 129, 130 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Betrayal in Antara]]'', a spiritual successor developed by Sierra\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{moby game|id=/betrayal-at-krondor}}\n* [http://mikesrpgcenter.com/krondor/index.html ''Betrayal at Krondor''] at Mike's RPG Center\n* [http://sourceforge.net/projects/xbak XBAK project], native play under X Window using original files\n\n{{The Riftwar Cycle}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Betrayal At Krondor}}\n[[Category:1993 video games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Raymond E. Feist]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Sierra Entertainment games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games based on novels]]\n[[Category:Games commercially released with DOSBox]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betrayal_at_Krondor"}
{"title_page": "Shulem Lemmer", "text_new": "{{notability|1=Biographies|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Shulem Lemmer''' (born 1990) is a [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] musician from New York. He is the first [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] Jew to sign a major record contract with a leading label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/belz-hasid-singer-shulem-lemmer-signed-to-major-label-living-the-perfect-dream/|title=Signed to major label, Belz Hasid singer Shulem Lemmer lives \u2018The Perfect Dream\u2019|last=Prince|first=Cathryn J.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLemmer was born and raised in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park Brooklyn]]. He is from a Hasidic family of the [[Belz (Hasidic dynasty)|Belz]] movement. Lemmer is the youngest of eight children. He studied at the Belzer Cheder in Borough Park and attended the [[Mir yeshiva|Mirrer Yeshiva]] in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1544544/historic-chassidic-singer-lands-major-record-deal-with-universal-music-group.html|title=HISTORIC: Chassidic Singer Lands MAJOR Record Deal With Universal Music Group|last=Editor|first=Y. W.|date=2018-06-26|website=The Yeshiva World|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> He began performing at small family events when he was 10 years old; when he was 13 his sister Tzippy, who later died in a car accident, encouraged him to perform on stage at a family wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/12/05/shulem-lemmers-perfect-world/|title=Shulem Lemmer\u2019s perfect world|date=2019-12-05|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> His older brother, Yanky, is a cantor in Manhattan's [[Lincoln Square Synagogue]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Cohen|first=Debra Nussbaum|url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-shulem-lemmer-first-ultra-orthodox-singer-to-get-a-major-record-deal-1.6618132|title=Meet the First ultra-Orthodox Singer to Get a Major Record Deal in the U.S.|date=2018-11-04|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBefore becoming a full-time singer, Lemmer was the director of marketing at a private company.\n\n== Musical career ==\nHe is the first Hasidic Jew to sign with a major record label, [[Universal Music Group]] under their [[Decca Gold]] imprint.  He consults with a team of rabbinic advisors; his contract stipulates that he can refuse a performance for any reason.<ref name=\":0\" /> The music on his debut album, ''The Perfect Dream,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/life/436074/an-unexpected-hasidic-pop-star-takes-the-stage/|title=With \"The Perfect Dream,\" An Unexpected Pop Star Takes The Stage|last=ConnellyDecember 9|first=Irene|last2=Truax|first2=2019Meredith|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> is produced by Jon Cohen and accompanied by London's Royal Philharmonic Orchestra.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/265477/universal-music-discovered-belzer-hasid-shulem-lemmer-on-youtube-they-just-released-his-first-singles|title=Universal Music Discovered Hasidic Singer Shulem Lemmer on YouTube. They Just Released His First Singles.|date=2018-07-02|work=Tablet Magazine|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2019/09/16/young-gifted-and-hasidic-tenor-to-sing-at-the-ofjcc/|title=Sensational Hasidic tenor Shulem coming to Palo Alto|last=Paull|first=Laura|date=2019-09-16|website=J.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Lemmer sang \u201c''[[God Bless America]]''\u201d at [[Citi Field]]s. That same month, Lemmer and his family were isolated on a [[JetBlue|Jet Blue]] flight from the Dominican Republic following a measles scare involving his daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-measles-hasidic-jetblue-jfk-dominican-republic-20190429-wm7p7f6oivbh5phpikfyzuqdde-story.html|title=Hasidic dad and daughter forced from flight over measles scare, sources say|last=Gartland|first=Michael|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe lives in Toms River, New Jersey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/07/18/shulem-lemmer-orthodox-jewish-record-deal/772807002/|title=Meet the Orthodox Jewish trailblazer from Toms River with a major record deal|last=Mikle|first=Jean|website=Asbury Park Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> He is married and has three children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amimagazine.org/2018/07/25/the-making-of-a-music-star/|website=www.amimagazine.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he was awarded a [[Jew in the City]] All-Star Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.5tjt.com/stars-shine-at-6th-annual-jew-in-the-city-all-stars-awards/|title=Stars Shine at 6th Annual Jew in the City All-Stars Awards|last=Online|first=5TJT|date=2020-01-13|website=The 5 Towns Jewish Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lincolncenter.org/show/jew-in-the-citys-6th-annual-all-star-awards|title=Lincoln Center|website=www.lincolncenter.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Jewish musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Hasidic entertainers]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language singers]]\n[[Category:Hasidic singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|1=Biographies|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Shulem Lemmer''' (born 1990) is a Hassidic musician from New York. He is the first ultra-Orthodox Jew to sign a major record contract with a leading label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/belz-hasid-singer-shulem-lemmer-signed-to-major-label-living-the-perfect-dream/|title=Signed to major label, Belz Hasid singer Shulem Lemmer lives \u2018The Perfect Dream\u2019|last=Prince|first=Cathryn J.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nLemmer was born and raised in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Boro Park Brooklyn]]. He is from a Hassidic family of the [[Belz (Hasidic dynasty)|Belz]] movement. Lemmer is the youngest of eight children. He studied at the Belzer Cheder in Borough Park and attended the [[Mir yeshiva|Mirrer Yeshiva]] in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/1544544/historic-chassidic-singer-lands-major-record-deal-with-universal-music-group.html|title=HISTORIC: Chassidic Singer Lands MAJOR Record Deal With Universal Music Group|last=Editor|first=Y. W.|date=2018-06-26|website=The Yeshiva World|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> He began performing at small family events when he was 10 years old; when he was 13 his sister Tzippy, who later died in a car accident, encouraged him to perform on stage at a family wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/12/05/shulem-lemmers-perfect-world/|title=Shulem Lemmer\u2019s perfect world|date=2019-12-05|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> His older brother, Yanky, is a cantor in Manhattan's [[Lincoln Square Synagogue]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Cohen|first=Debra Nussbaum|url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/.premium-shulem-lemmer-first-ultra-orthodox-singer-to-get-a-major-record-deal-1.6618132|title=Meet the First ultra-Orthodox Singer to Get a Major Record Deal in the U.S.|date=2018-11-04|work=Haaretz|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBefore becoming a full-time singer, Lemmer was the director of marketing at a private company.\n\n== Musical career ==\nHe is the first Hasidic Jew to sign with a major record label, [[Universal Music Group]] under their [[Decca Gold]] imprint.  He consults with a team of rabbinic advisors; his contract stipulates that he can refuse a performance for any reason.<ref name=\":0\" /> The music on his debut album, ''The Perfect Dream,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/life/436074/an-unexpected-hasidic-pop-star-takes-the-stage/|title=With \"The Perfect Dream,\" An Unexpected Pop Star Takes The Stage|last=ConnellyDecember 9|first=Irene|last2=Truax|first2=2019Meredith|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> is produced by Jon Cohen and accompanied by London's Royal Philharmonic Orchestra.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/265477/universal-music-discovered-belzer-hasid-shulem-lemmer-on-youtube-they-just-released-his-first-singles|title=Universal Music Discovered Hasidic Singer Shulem Lemmer on YouTube. They Just Released His First Singles.|date=2018-07-02|work=Tablet Magazine|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jweekly.com/2019/09/16/young-gifted-and-hasidic-tenor-to-sing-at-the-ofjcc/|title=Sensational Hasidic tenor Shulem coming to Palo Alto|last=Paull|first=Laura|date=2019-09-16|website=J.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Lemmer sang \u201c''[[God Bless America]]''\u201d at [[Citi Field]]s. That same month, Lemmer and his family were isolated on a [[JetBlue|Jet Blue]] flight from the Dominican Republic following a measles scare involving his daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-measles-hasidic-jetblue-jfk-dominican-republic-20190429-wm7p7f6oivbh5phpikfyzuqdde-story.html|title=Hasidic dad and daughter forced from flight over measles scare, sources say|last=Gartland|first=Michael|website=nydailynews.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe lives in Toms River, New Jersey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.app.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/07/18/shulem-lemmer-orthodox-jewish-record-deal/772807002/|title=Meet the Orthodox Jewish trailblazer from Toms River with a major record deal|last=Mikle|first=Jean|website=Asbury Park Press|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> He is married and has three children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amimagazine.org/2018/07/25/the-making-of-a-music-star/|website=www.amimagazine.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he was awarded a [[Jew in the City]] All-Star Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.5tjt.com/stars-shine-at-6th-annual-jew-in-the-city-all-stars-awards/|title=Stars Shine at 6th Annual Jew in the City All-Stars Awards|last=Online|first=5TJT|date=2020-01-13|website=The 5 Towns Jewish Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lincolncenter.org/show/jew-in-the-citys-6th-annual-all-star-awards|title=Lincoln Center|website=www.lincolncenter.org|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:American Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Jewish musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Hasidic entertainers]]\n[[Category:Yiddish-language singers]]\n[[Category:Hasidic singers]]\n", "name_user": "Newmila", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed spelling for consistency (\"Hasidic\" was sometimes spelled with one s, sometimes with two).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shulem_Lemmer"}
{"title_page": "Ulrich of Attems", "text_new": "'''Ulrich of Attems''' (Ulrich von Attems, circa 1082 in Attimis, Udine&nbsp;- 1170) was an Italian nobleman from the family of [[Attems]]. He also served as the vicar (and de facto head of) of Tuscany and Spoleto between 1139 and 1152.\n\nUlrich was the son Conrad of Attems (1052-1106), who was a Minister of [[Conrad III of Germany|King Conrad III]], who regarded himself as the heir of [[Henry V, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry V]]. Therefore, Ulrich tried in 1128\u20131130 in opposition to the popes to seize the vast Italian properties of [[Matilda of Tuscany]]. In 1137, [[Henry X, Duke of Bavaria]] (Henry the Proud) of the [[House of Welf|Welf family]] was named the Margrave of Tuscany by [[Lothair II, Holy Roman Emperor]]. Shortly before the death of Henry in 1139, Ulrich was appointed by Conrad (who succeeded Lothair) as vicar there.<ref>von Freising, Otto, Chronica, lib. VII, chapter 23</ref> This led to further conflicts between Konrad and the Welf family.<ref>Gebhardt, Bruno, Handbuch der deutschen Geschichte: Zw\u00f6lftes Jahrhundert, 1125-1198, p. 67</ref>  Ulrich as vicar ruled over Tuscany and Spoleto until 1152.\n\nDuring his time in Tuscany, the Normans from the Kingdom of Sicily attacked and conquered northern Abruzzo (at that time part of the [[Duchy of Spoleto]]) in 1140.  King [[Roger II of Sicily]] sent his son [[Alfonso of Capua]] supported by his eldest son [[Roger III, Duke of Apulia]], across the border at Pescara which overwhelmed the defensive forces against them. The resulting territory up to the Tronto River was then incorporated into the Kingdom of Sicily.<ref>Matthew, Donald, The Norman Kingdom of Sicily, University of Cambridge Press (1992) pp.53-54</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Ulrich had difficulty maintaining and consolidating his power in Tuscany. After the death of Conrad in 1152, another member of the Welf family, [[Welf VI]] was named the Margrave of Tuscany and Duke of the remainder of Spoleto by [[Frederick I, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick I]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Duke of Spoleto]]\n* [[List of rulers of Tuscany]]\n* {{ill|Mathildische G\u00fcter|de}}\n* [[Norman conquest of southern Italy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1082 births]]\n[[Category:1170 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ulrich of Attems''' (Ulrich von Attems) (born circa 1082 (Attimis, Udine) - died 1170) was an Italian nobleman from the family of [[Attems]]. He also served as the vicar (and de facto head of) of Tuscany and Spoleto between 1139 and 1152.\n\nUlrich was the son Conrad of Attems (1052-1106), who was a Minister of [[Conrad III of Germany|King Conrad III]], who regarded himself as the heir of [[Henry V, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry V]]. Therefore, Ulrich tried in 1128-1130 in opposition to the popes to seize the vast Italian properties of [[Matilda of Tuscany]]. In 1137, [[Henry X, Duke of Bavaria]] (Henry the Proud) of the [[House of Welf|Welf family]] was named the Margrave of Tuscany by [[Lothair II, Holy Roman Emperor]]. Shortly before the death of Henry in 1139, Ulrich was appointed by Conrad (who succeeded Lothair) as vicar there.<ref>von Freising, Otto, Chronica, lib. VII, chapter 23</ref> This led to further conflicts between Konrad and the Welf family.<ref>Gebhardt, Bruno, Handbuch der deutschen Geschichte: Zw\u00f6lftes Jahrhundert, 1125-1198, p. 67</ref>  Ulrich as vicar ruled over Tuscany and Spoleto until 1152.\n\nDuring his time in Tuscany, the Normans from the Kingdom of Sicily attacked and conquered northern Abruzzo (at that time part of the [[Duchy of Spoleto]]) in 1140.  King [[Roger II of Sicily]] sent his son [[Alfonso of Capua]] supported by his eldest son [[Roger III, Duke of Apulia]], across the border at Pescara which overwhelmed the defensive forces against them. The resulting territory up to the Tronto River was then incorporated into the Kingdom of Sicily.<ref>Matthew, Donald, The Norman Kingdom of Sicily, University of Cambridge Press (1992) pp.53-54</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Ulrich had difficulty maintaining and consolidating his power in Tuscany. After the death of Conrad in 1152, another member of the Welf family, [[Welf VI]] was named the Margrave of Tuscany and Duke of the remainder of Spoleto by [[Frederick I, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick I]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[:de:Ulrich von Attems]] (in German)\n* [[List of rulers of Tuscany]]\n* [[:de:Mathildische G\u00fcter]] (in German)\n* [[Norman conquest of southern Italy]]\n* [[Duke of Spoleto]]\n\n[[Category:1082 births]]\n[[Category:1170 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian nobility]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1128-1130 \u2192 1128\u20131130", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulrich_of_Attems"}
{"title_page": "La Boca Formation", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = La Boca Formation\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| period         = Lower Jurassic\n| age            = Middle [[Toarcian]]<ref name=\"Toarcian\"/>\n| prilithology   =\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Tamaulipas]]\n| country        = [[Mexico]]\n| coordinates    =\n| unitof         = \n| subunits       =\n| underlies      = [[La Joya Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Huizachal Formation]]\n| thickness      = \n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''La Boca Formation''' is a [[geological formation]] in [[Tamaulipas]] state, northeast Mexico. It was trougth to date back to the [[Early Jurassic]], concretely the Pliensbachian stage epoch.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=K2an9yd2aq4C&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=La+Joya+Formation+mexico&source=bl&ots=_eLC3ByJgN&sig=xq2OdUOaIYumsfrNB3dw1MSGknE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwia9PqB4ubRAhXp7IMKHYb2AygQ6AEIHzAB#v=onepage&q=La%20Joya%20Formation%20mexico&f=false   Mesozoic Sedimentary and Tectonic History of North-central Mexico, Issue 340], pg 206; \nedited by Claudio Bartolini, James Lee Wilson, Timothy Frost Lawton.</ref><ref name=\"middlejurassicdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Middle Jurassic, North America).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 537\u2013538. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref> Altrougth, the latest studies had proven that the local Vulcanism, related to the aperture of the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and the several Rift Events, that continue until the [[Bajocian]] where developed until the Latest Pliensbachian, with tha fossil taxa deposited on the rocks above.<ref>Boschman, L., Van Hinsbergen, D. J., Langereis, C. G., Molina-Garza, R. S., & Kimbrough, D. L. (2017, December). Paleomagnetic Constraints on the Tectonic History of the Mesozoic Ophiolite and Arc Terranes of Western Mexico. In AGU Fall Meeting Abstracts.</ref> Due to succesions of [[Aalenian]] depositional sistems on the upper layers of the [[Huizachal Canyon]], has been delimited the formation to the [[Toarcian]] stage, being the regional equivalent of the Moroccan [[Azilal Formation]].<ref name=\"Toarcian\">Martini, M., & Ortega-Guti\u00e9rrez, F. (2018). Tectono-stratigraphic evolution of eastern Mexico during the break-up of Pangea: A review. Earth-Science Reviews, 183, 38-55.</ref>\n\n== Fossil record ==\n=== Unclassified Diapsida ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n''[[Tamaulipasaurus]]''<ref name=\"Tamaulipasaurus\">Clark, J. M. (1994). A new burrowing diapsid from the Jurassic La Boca Formation of Tamaulipas, Mexico. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 14(2), 180-195.</ref>\n|\n''T. morenoi''\n|\nDinosaur National Monument South, Huizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nSkull and several fragmentary remains\n|\nA strange burrowing [[Diapsid]]: \"Burrowing diapsid representing a heretofore unknown clade\"<ref name=\"Tamaulipasaurus\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Synapsida ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n''[[Bocaconodon]]''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n| \n''B. tamaulipensis''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\nJim's Joy, Huizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nTeeth\n|\nA basal [[Mammaliaform]]<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n| rowspan=\"99\" |\n|-\n| \n''[[Bocatherium]]''<ref name=\"fraser\">{{cite book |editor=Fraser, Nicholas |editor2=Sues, Hans-Dieter | title=In the Shadow of the Dinosaurs: Early Mesozoic Tetrapods | publisher=Cambridge University Press | year=1994 | isbn=0-521-45242-2}}</ref> \n|\n''B. mexicanum''<ref name=\"fraser\" />\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nIGM 3492, Skull\n|\nA [[Tritylodontid]]<ref name=\"fraser\" />\n|-\n| \n''[[Huasteconodon]]''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\n''H. wiblei''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nTeeth\n|\nA [[Gobiconodontidae|Gobiconodont]]<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|-\n| \n''[[Victoriaconodon]]''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\n''V. inaequalis''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\nRene's Roost, Huizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nTeeth\n|\nA [[Triconodontidae|Triconodontid]]<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|-\n| \nUnnamed [[Mammaliaform]]s (IGM 6622,IGM 6855, and IGM 6856)<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n|\nIndeterminate\n|\n*Cementario, Huizachal Canyon\n*Casa de Fidencio, Huizachal Canyon\n|\nLower Part \n|\nIGM 6855, partial right dentary; IGM 6856, left dentary; IGM 6622, partial right dentary\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Sphenodontia ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n''[[Cynosphenodon]]''<ref>Reynoso, V. H. (1996). A Middle Jurassic Sphenodon-like sphenodontian (Diapsida: Lepidosauria) from Huizachal Canyon, Tamaulipas, Mexico. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 16(2), 210-221.</ref>\n|\n''C. huizachalensis''\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nJaws & teeth of various specimens\n|\nA [[Sphenodontidae]] [[Rhynchocephalia]]n.<ref>Reynoso, V. H. (2003). Growth patterns and ontogenetic variation of the teeth and jaws of the Middle Jurassic sphenodontian Cynosphenodon huizachalensis (Reptilia: Rhynchocephalia). Canadian Journal of Earth Sciences, 40(4), 609-619.</ref>\n|-\n| \n''[[Sphenovipera]]''<ref name=\"Sphenovipera\">Reynoso, V.H. 2005. Possible evidence of a venom apparatus in a Middle Jurassic sphenodontian from the Huizachal red beds of Tamaulipas, Mexico. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 25: 646\u2013653. {{doi|10.1671/0272-4634(2005)025[0646:PEOAVA]2.0.CO;2}}</ref>\n|\n''S. jimmysjoyi''<ref name=\"Sphenovipera\" />\n|\nJim's Joy, Huizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nIGM 6076, right lower jaw\n|\nA venomous [[Sphenodont]]<ref name=\"Sphenovipera\" />\n|-\n| \n''[[Zapatadon]]''<ref>V.-H. Reynoso and J. M. Clark. 1998. A dwarf sphenodontian from the Jurassic La Boca Formation of Tamaulipas, Mexico. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 18:333-339</ref>\n|\n''Z. ejidoensis''\n|\nTierra Buena, W Huizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nJaws\n|\nA dwarf [[Sphenodont]]\n|-\n|}\n\n\n=== Pterosauria ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n''\"[[Dimorphodon]]\"''<ref>Clark, J. M., Hopson, J. A., Fastovsky, D. E., & Montellano, M. (1998). Foot posture in a primitive pterosaur. Nature, 391(6670), 886-889.</ref>\n|\n''\"D.\" weintraubi''\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nFragmentary skeleton of a large rhamphorhynchoid that includes a remarkably preserved pes.\n|\nA [[Pterosaur]] of uncertain phylogenetic placement, being originally proposed as a member of the genus [[Dimorphodon]], altrougth, has some great differences with the original holotype, and Dimorphodon is a lower Liassic Genus. Most recent analises place it on different positions on [[Novialoidea]].<ref>Britt, B. B., Dalla Vecchia, F. M., Chure, D. J., Engelmann, G. F., Whiting, M. F., & Scheetz, R. D. (2018). Caelestiventus hanseni gen. et sp. nov. extends the desert-dwelling pterosaur record back 65 million years. Nature ecology & evolution, 2(9), 1386-1392.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n\n=== Crocodrylomorpha ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \nUnnamed [[Crocodyliform]]s<ref name=\"fraser\" /><ref>V.-H. Reynoso. 2006. Research on fossil amphibians and reptiles in Mexico, from 1869 to early 2004 (including marine forms but excluding pterosaurs, dinosaurs, and obviously, birds). In F. J. Vega, T. G. Nyborg, M. Del Carmen Perrilliat, M. Montellano-Ballesteros, S. R. S. Cevallos-Ferriz, S. A. Quiroz-Barroso (eds.), Studies on Mexican Paleontology 24:209-231</ref>\n|\nIndeterminate\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nSkull fragment \n|\nNon compared\n|-\n| \n[[Metasuchia]]<ref name=\"fraser\" />\n|\n? Metasuchia indeterminate\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nIGM 3498 & additional specimens. Partial skulls and postcranial skeletons \n|\nNon compared\n|-\n|}\n\n\n=== Dinosauria ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n\"[[Syntarsus]]\"<ref name=\"Theropod dinosaurs\">R. C. Munter and J. M. Clark. 2006. Theropod dinosaurs from the Early Jurassic of Huizachal Canyon, Mexico. In M. T. Carrano, T. J. Gaudin, R. W. Blob, J. R. Wible (eds.), Amniote paleobiology: perspectives on the evolution of mammals, birds, and reptiles. University of Chicago Press, Chicago 53-7</ref>\n|\n\"Syntarsus\" mexicanum <ref>Gonz\u00e1lez, De Stefano and Hernandez, 2002. [unknown title] in Gonz\u00e1lez and  St\u00e9fano (eds.). F\u00f3siles de M\u00e9xico- Coahuila: Una ventana a trav\u00e9s del tiempo.  Gobierno del Estado de Coahuila. 214-215.</ref>\n|\nCasa de Fidencio, Huizachal Canyon\n|\nLower Part \n|\n(IGM 6624) partial twelfth dorsal vertebra, partial thirteenth dorsal vertebra, partial synsacrum, incomplete fused pelvis\n|\nAn indeterminate [[Coelophysoidea]]n.\n|-\n| \n[[Ceratosauria]]<ref name=\"Theropod dinosaurs\"/>\n|\nCeratosauria Indeterminate\n|\nCasa de Fidencio, Huizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nIGM 6625, craneal fragmentary elements\n|\nA possible basal ceratosaur related with the African [[Berberosaurus]].\n|-\n| \n[[Neotheropoda]]<ref name=\"Theropod dinosaurs\"/>\n|\nNeotheropoda Indeterminate\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nIsolated teeth\n|\nSeveral morphotypes, maybe related with [[Coelophysoidea]], [[Dilophosauridae]] or [[Tetanureae]].<ref name=\"Theropod dinosaurs\"/>\n|-\n| \n[[Heterodontosauridae]]<ref name=JMCetal94>{{cite book |last=Clark |first=James |author2=Montellano, Marisol |author3=Hopson, James A. |author4=Hernandez, Rene |author5=Fastovsky, David A. |editor=Fraser, N.C. |editor2=Sues H.-D. |chapter=An Early or Middle Jurassic tetrapod assemblage from the La Boca Formation, northeastern Mexico |title=In The Shadow of the Dinosaurs: Early Mesozoic Tetrapods |year=1994 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=295\u2013302 |isbn=0-521-45899-4}}</ref>\n|\ncf. Heterodontosaurus sp.\n|\nHuizachal Canyon \n| \nLower Part\n|\nTeeth\n|\nAn [[Ornithischia]]n of the family [[Heterodontosauridae]].\n|-\n| \n?[[Sauropodomorpha]]<ref name=\"middlejurassicdistribution\" /><ref name=\"Theropod dinosaurs\"/>\n|\n?Sauropodomorpha indeterminate\n|\nRene's Roost, Huizachal Canyon \n|\nLower Part \n|\nLarge bone fragments\n|\nA possible Basal Sauropodomorph.\n|-\n|}\n\n\n== See also ==\n* {{C|Jurassic Mexico}}\n* [[List of dinosaur-bearing rock formations]]\n* [[List of pterosaur-bearing stratigraphic units]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Mexico|Paleontology|Dinosaurs}}\n\n{{-}}\n\n[[Category:Jurassic Mexico]]\n[[Category:Geography of Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:Early Jurassic North America]]\n[[Category:Middle Jurassic North America]]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Natural history of Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Jurassic System of North America]]\n\n\n{{paleo-site-stub}}\n{{Mexico-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = La Boca Formation\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| period         = Middle Jurassic\n| age            = [[Early Jurassic]], Pliensbachian <ref name=\"mammal\">Montellano, M., J. A. Hopson, and J. M. Clark. 2008. Late Early Jurassic mammaliaforms from Huizachal Canyon, Tamaulipas, Mexico. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 28:1130\u20131143. [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1671/0272-4634-28.4.1130]</ref>\n| prilithology   =\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Tamaulipas]]\n| country        = [[Mexico]]\n| coordinates    =\n| unitof         = \n| subunits       =\n| underlies      = [[La Joya Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Huizachal Formation]]\n| thickness      = \n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''La Boca Formation''' is a [[geological formation]] in [[Tamaulipas]] state, northeast Mexico. It dates back to the [[Early Jurassic]], concretely the Pliensbachian stage epoch.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=K2an9yd2aq4C&pg=PA221&lpg=PA221&dq=La+Joya+Formation+mexico&source=bl&ots=_eLC3ByJgN&sig=xq2OdUOaIYumsfrNB3dw1MSGknE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwia9PqB4ubRAhXp7IMKHYb2AygQ6AEIHzAB#v=onepage&q=La%20Joya%20Formation%20mexico&f=false   Mesozoic Sedimentary and Tectonic History of North-central Mexico, Issue 340], pg 206; \nedited by Claudio Bartolini, James Lee Wilson, Timothy Frost Lawton.</ref><ref name=\"middlejurassicdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Middle Jurassic, North America).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 537\u2013538. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref>\n\n== Fossil record ==\n=== Vertebrate fauna ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" |'''[[Vertebrate]]s of the La Boca Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Abundance\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| \n''[[Bocaconodon]]''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n| \n''B. tamaulipensis''<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n| \n| \n|\n|A basal [[Mammaliaform]]<ref name=\"mammal\" />\n| rowspan=\"99\" |\n|-\n| \n''[[Bocatherium]]''<re