{"title_page": "Nicholas Monsarrat", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{distinguish|Nicol\u00e1s Monserrat}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Nicholas Monsarrat\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = Lieutenant Commander\n| honorific_suffix = FRSL RNVR\n| image            = File:Nicholas Monsarrat.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Commemorative plaque on [[Rodney Street, Liverpool]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = Nicholas John Turney Monsarrat\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=yes|1910|03|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Liverpool, England]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1979|08|08|1910|03|22}}\n| death_place      = London\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Lawyer, writer, sailor\n| language         = English\n| nationality      = English\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Trinity College, Cambridge University]]\n| period           = \n| genre            = Maritime fiction\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''[[The Cruel Sea (novel)|The Cruel Sea]]''\n| spouse           = Eileen Rowland, Phillipa Crosby, and Ann Griffiths\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = Marc, Anthony, and Max\n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = 1934\u20131979\n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n[[Lieutenant Commander]] '''Nicholas John Turney Monsarrat''' [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]] [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve|RNVR]] (22 March 1910{{spaced ndash}}8 August 1979) was a British novelist known today for his [[sea stories]], particularly ''[[The Cruel Sea (novel)|The Cruel Sea]]'' (1951) and ''Three Corvettes'' (1942\u201345), but perhaps best known internationally for his novels, ''The Tribe That Lost Its Head'' and its sequel, ''Richer Than All His Tribe''.<ref name=britishwriters>{{Citation|author=Krueger, Christine L. |title=Encyclopedia of British Writers, 19th and 20th Centuries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dnqi3gRxgvQC&pg=RA1-PA257#v=onepage&q&f=false |page=257 |year=2003 |publisher=Facts on File |isbn=0-8160-4670-0 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMonsarrat was born on [[Rodney Street, Liverpool|Rodney Street]]<ref>Liverpool Record Office Annual Report 2008\u20132009{{full citation needed|date=October 2014}}</ref> in [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], to parents Sir Keith Monsarrat, surgeon,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evolve360.co.uk/Data/10/PageLMHS/Bulletin22/carmichael.pdf |title=Bio|website=evolve360.co.uk}}</ref> and Ada Marguerita Turney Waldegrave.<ref name=britishwriters /> Monsarrat was educated at [[Winchester College|Winchester]] and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicholas Monsarrat|url=http://www.historicnavalfiction.com/related-authors/1719-nicholas-monsarrat|website=Historic Naval Fiction|accessdate=11 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817100912/https://www.historicnavalfiction.com/related-authors/1719-nicholas-monsarrat|archivedate=17 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He intended to practise law. The law failed to inspire him, however, and he turned instead to writing, moving to London and supporting himself as a freelance writer for newspapers while writing four novels and a play in the space of five years (1934\u20131939). He later commented in his autobiography that the 1931 [[Invergordon Mutiny|Invergordon Naval Mutiny]] influenced his interest in politics and social and economic issues after college.\n\n==Wartime service==\nThough a [[pacifism|pacifist]], Monsarrat served in World War II, first as a member of an ambulance brigade and then as a member of the [[History of the Royal Naval Reserve#Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve|Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve (RNVR)]]. His lifelong love of sailing made him a capable naval officer, and he served with distinction in a series of small warships ([[corvette]]s and [[frigate]]s), assigned to escort [[convoy]]s and protect them from enemy attack. Monsarrat ended the war as commander of a frigate, and drew on his wartime experience in his postwar [[sea stories]]. It has been alleged that during his wartime service, Monsarrat claimed to have seen the [[ghost ship]] ''[[Flying Dutchman]]'' while sailing the Pacific, near the location where the young [[King George V]] had seen her in 1881. No mention was made of this in his autobiographies however, and the ship he was supposedly serving on (HMS ''Jubilee'') did not, in fact, exist.\n\nResigning his wartime commission in 1946, Monsarrat entered the diplomatic service. He was posted at first to [[Johannesburg]], South Africa and then, in 1953, to [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref name=\"obit\"/> He turned to writing full-time in 1959, settling first on [[Guernsey]], in the [[Channel Islands]], and later on the [[Malta|Maltese]] island of [[Gozo]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=J. Y.|title=Author Nicholas Monsarrat Dies|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1979/08/09/author-nicholas-monsarrat-dies/c96551dd-e24c-4935-843f-3c6e3a7f3d78/|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=20 April 2017|date=9 August 1979}}</ref>\n\n===Ranks ===\n* July 1940: Sub-Lieutenant\n* October 1940: Lieutenant\n* December 1943: Lieutenant Commander\n\n===Posts===\n* Aug 1940 \u2013 Dec 1941: 1st Lt, HMS ''Campanula'' ({{sclass2-|Flower|corvette|1}})\n* Feb 1942 \u2013 Feb 1943: 1st Lt, HMS ''Guillemot'' ([[Kingfisher-class sloop|''Kingfisher''-class corvette]])\n* Mar 1943 \u2013 Oct 1943: CO, HMS ''Shearwater'' (''Kingfisher''-class corvette)\n* Dec 1943 \u2013 Mar 1944: CO, HMS ''Ettrick'' ({{sclass2-|River|frigate|1}})\n* Apr 1944 \u2013 Dec 1944: CO, {{HMS|Perim|K593|6}} ({{sclass2-|Colony|frigate|1}}: a US-built version of the River class)\n* Dec 1944 \u2013 Jul 1945: Dept. of Naval Information\n\n\"HMS ''Flower''\" and \"HMS ''Compass Rose''\" were fictional Flower-class corvettes in the short story ''H M Corvette'' (1942) and the novel ''[[The Cruel Sea (book)|The Cruel Sea]]'' (1951)\n\n\"HMS ''Dipper''\" and \"HMS ''Winger''\" were fictional ''Kingfisher''-class corvettes in the stories ''East Coast Corvette'' (1943) and ''Corvette Command'' (1944), (republished with ''H M Corvette'' as ''Three Corvettes'' in 1945).\n\n\"HMS ''River''\" and \"HMS ''Saltash''\" were fictional River-class frigates in ''H M Frigate'' (1946), and the novel ''The Cruel Sea'' (1951).  (In the [[The Cruel Sea (1953 film)|1953 film version]] HMS ''Saltash'' was depicted by {{sclass2-|Castle|corvette|1}}: {{HMS|Portchester Castle|K362|6}}, and hence named \"''Saltash Castle''\").\n\n===Awards===\n* June 43: Mentioned in Dispatches\n\n== Work ==\nMonsarrat's first three novels, published in 1934\u20131937 and now out of print, were realistic treatments of modern social problems informed by his leftist politics. ''The Visitor'', his only play, fell into the same category.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite web|last1=Hauptfuhrer|first1=Fred|title=To Ann and Nicholas Monsarrat, the Sea Is Never Cruel: It Inspires His Fiction and Their Idyll|url=http://people.com/archive/to-ann-and-nicholas-monsarrat-the-sea-is-never-cruel-it-inspires-his-fiction-and-their-idyll-vol-12-no-1/|website=People|publisher=People|accessdate=20 April 2017|date=2 July 1979}}</ref> His fourth novel and first major work, ''This Is the Schoolroom'', took a different approach. The story of a young, idealistic, aspiring writer coming to grips with the \"real world\" for the first time, it is at least partly autobiographical.\n\n''The Cruel Sea'' (1951), Monsarrat's first postwar novel, is widely regarded as his finest work, and is the only one of his novels that is still widely read. Based on his own wartime service, it followed the young naval officer Keith Lockhart through a series of postings in corvettes and frigates. It was one of the first novels to depict life aboard the vital, but unglamorous, \"small ships\" of World War II\u2014ships for which the sea was as much a threat as the Germans. Monsarrat's short-story collections ''H.M.S. Marlborough Will Enter Harbour'' (1949), and ''The Ship That Died of Shame'' (1959, made into a film of the [[The Ship That Died of Shame|same name]]), mined the same literary vein, and gained popularity by association with ''The Cruel Sea''.\n\nThe similar ''Three Corvettes'' (1945 and 1953) comprising ''H.M. Corvette'' (set aboard a Flower-class corvette in the [[North Atlantic]]), ''East Coast Corvette'' (as First Lieutenant of HMS ''Guillemot'') and ''Corvette Command'' (as Commanding Officer of {{HMS|Shearwater|L39|6}}) is actually an anthology of three true-experience stories he published during the war years and shows appropriate care for what the [[Censorship|Censor]] might say. Thus ''Guillemot'' appears under the pseudonym ''Dipper'' and ''Shearwater'' under the pseudonym ''Winger'' in the book. ''H M Frigate'' is similar but deals with his time in command of two frigates. His use of the name ''[[Dipper]]'' could allude to his formative years when summer holidays were spent with his family at [[Trearddur Bay]]. They were members of the famous sailing club based there, and he recounted much of this part of his life in a book ''My brother Denys''. Denys Monsarrat was killed in [[Egypt]] during the middle part of the war whilst his brother was serving with the Royal Navy. Another tale recounts his bringing his ship into [[Trearddur Bay]] during the war for old times' sake.\n\nMonsarrat's more famous novels, notably ''The Tribe That Lost Its Head'' (1956) and its sequel ''Richer Than All His Tribe'' (1968), drew on his experience in the diplomatic service and make important reference to the [[Colonialism|colonial]] experience of Britain in Africa. Several have peripheral connections to the sea: ''The Nylon Pirates'' (1960) tells a story of piracy aboard a modern ocean liner, not pirates in the traditional meaning of the word, but card-sharps, and ''A Fair Day's Work'' (1964) deals with labour unrest in a shipyard. ''The Kappillan of Malta'' (1973) is as much a story of a place, the island of [[Malta]], as it is of a priest on that island during the terrible days of World War II.\n\nHis book ''The Story of Esther Costello'' (1952), later made into a film \nof the [[The Story of Esther Costello|same name]], while perceived as an uncomplimentary take on the life of [[Helen Keller]] and her teachers and assistants, is really an expos\u00e9 of sleazy practices and exploitation of real causes in the fundraising racket, similar to criticisms of [[televangelism]].<ref>[http://www.filmsofcrawford.com/id112.html]{{dead link|date=March 2018}}</ref> It caused a minor public outcry when it first appeared, and Keller's staff considered suing him, then tried to keep the book off the shelves.<ref>Lash, Joseph, ''Helen and Teacher'', Addison Wesley 1997, pp. 732\u2013738.</ref>\n\nHis final work, unfinished at the time of his death but published in its incomplete form, was a two-volume historical novel titled ''The Master Mariner.'' Based on the legend of the [[Wandering Jew]], it told the story of an [[Elizabethan era|Elizabethan]] English seaman who, as punishment for a terrible act of cowardice, is doomed to sail the world's seas until the end of time. His hero participates in critical moments in history; Monsarrat used him to illustrate the central role of seamen.\n\n===Autobiography===\nTwo non-fiction books, ''Life is a Four Letter Word: Breaking In'' (London, 1966) and ''Life is a Four Letter Word: Breaking Out'' (London, 1970) comprise Monsarrat's autobiography.\n\n==Death==\nNicholas Monsarrat died of cancer on 8 August 1979 in London.<ref name=\"obit\">{{cite web|last1=Pace|first1=Eric|title=Nicholas Monsarrat, Novelist, Dies; Wrote War Epic 'The Cruel Sea'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/08/09/archives/nicholas-monsarrat-novelist-dies-wrote-war-epic-the-cruel-sea-wrote.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|accessdate=20 April 2017|page=17|date=4 Aug 1979}}</ref> The [[Royal Navy]] co-operated with his wish to be buried at sea.\n\nThe two naval ratings responsible for the lifting of the cask at his burial were AB Graham Savage and AB Stephen Knight, aboard [[HMS Scylla (F71)]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{div col}}\n* ''Think of Tomorrow'' (1934)\n* ''At First Sight'' (1935)\n* ''The Whipping Boy'' (1937)\n* ''This is the Schoolroom'' (1939)\n* ''The Visitor'' \u2013 play\n* ''H.M. Corvette'' (1942)\n* ''East Coast Corvette'' (1943)\n* ''Corvette Command'' (1944)\n* ''Three Corvettes'' (1945) (a consolidation of ''H.M. Corvette'', ''East Coast Corvette'' and ''Corvette Command'')\n* ''Leave Cancelled'' (1945)\n* ''Three Corvettes'' (1945 and 1953)\n* ''H. M. Frigate'' (1946)\n* ''Depends on What You Mean by Love'' (1947)\n* ''H.M.S. Marlborough Will Enter Harbour'' (1947)\n* ''My Brother Denys'' (1948)\n* ''[[The Cruel Sea (novel)|The Cruel Sea]]'' (1951)\n* ''The Story of Esther Costello'' (1952)\n* ''The Boy's Book of the Sea'' \u2013 as editor (1954)\n* ''Canada from Coast to Coast'' (1955)\n* ''Castle Garac'' (1955)\n* ''The Tribe That Lost Its Head'' (1956)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article84391457 |title=THE \"CRUEL SEA\" MAN GOES TO AFRICA Monsarrat writes a `let-down'. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=13 October 1956 |accessdate=10 July 2012 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* ''The Boy's Book of the Commonwealth'' \u2013 as editor (1957)\n* ''The Ship That Died of Shame, and Other Stories'' (1959) (comprising ''The Ship That Died of Shame''; ''Oh To Be In England!''; ''The Reconciliation''; ''The List'';